1
00:01:20,880 --> 00:01:25,078
Hear ye, hear ye, hear ye.

2
00:01:25,251 --> 00:01:28,812
Ladies and gentlemen,
this station has the honor to present...

3
00:01:28,988 --> 00:01:34,927
<i>...a weekly report on the New York scene
by Alexander Woollcott, The Town Crier.</i>

4
00:01:35,562 --> 00:01:37,655
This is Woollcott speaking.

5
00:01:37,831 --> 00:01:41,892
This evening, instead of reporting to you
on the new plays along Broadway...

6
00:01:42,068 --> 00:01:44,832
...I want to say a word about
the swarm of young hopefuls...

7
00:01:45,004 --> 00:01:46,801
...who arrive in New York each year...

8
00:01:46,973 --> 00:01:50,534
...determined to make good on the stage
if it takes a leg.

9
00:01:50,710 --> 00:01:54,874
I have here over 1000 letters
from such young people...

10
00:01:55,048 --> 00:01:57,346
...asking what to do, where to start.

11
00:01:57,517 --> 00:01:59,144
Every one of these people...

12
00:01:59,319 --> 00:02:03,653
...thinks that he has more talent
than 90 percent of the actors on Broadway.

13
00:02:03,823 --> 00:02:07,315
Broadway. They call it
"The Great White Way."

14
00:02:07,494 --> 00:02:11,726
<i>But it shines with a radiance
no electrical company can inspire.</i>

15
00:02:11,898 --> 00:02:13,957
<i>It comes from the likes of you.</i>

16
00:02:14,134 --> 00:02:17,194
<i>One word of advice,
take what you can get.</i>

17
00:02:17,370 --> 00:02:19,998
<i>Grab the chances as they come along.</i>

18
00:02:20,173 --> 00:02:23,301
<i>Act in hallways, sing in doorways...</i>

19
00:02:23,476 --> 00:02:26,104
<i>... and if you have to, dance in cellars.</i>

20
00:02:34,053 --> 00:02:36,214
Hello, everybody. How do you do?

21
00:02:36,389 --> 00:02:38,949
We're gonna do a song and a dance
and all for you.

22
00:02:39,125 --> 00:02:41,025
Never seen a better crowd at any place.

23
00:02:41,194 --> 00:02:43,458
We just wanna see you
have a smile on your face.

24
00:02:43,630 --> 00:02:46,326
So here comes our bag of tricks.
We turn on the show.

25
00:02:46,499 --> 00:02:49,059
Drop the nickel in, Nicky,
and here we go.

26
00:02:54,707 --> 00:02:55,969
<i>Hey! Hey!</i>

27
00:02:56,142 --> 00:02:59,236
<i>New York, New York
Fascinating city</i>

28
00:02:59,412 --> 00:03:02,711
<i>Magic castles rising in the air</i>

29
00:03:02,882 --> 00:03:06,181
<i>Wall Street, Broadway
Guys are sittin' pretty</i>

30
00:03:06,352 --> 00:03:09,150
<i>Every window hides a millionaire</i>

31
00:03:09,689 --> 00:03:13,125
<i>So when defeatists holler
"There's no chance"</i>

32
00:03:13,293 --> 00:03:17,559
<i>Just tell them this
But with a dirty glance</i>

33
00:03:18,698 --> 00:03:22,395
<i>Once Mr. Woolworth
Didn't have a dime</i>

34
00:03:22,569 --> 00:03:26,300
<i>And Irving Berlin
Didn't have a rhyme</i>

35
00:03:26,472 --> 00:03:29,373
<i>And Thomas Dewey
Didn't have a crime</i>

36
00:03:29,542 --> 00:03:33,569
<i>But anything can happen in New York</i>

37
00:03:34,280 --> 00:03:37,875
<i>Once Rockefeller
Didn't have that oil</i>

38
00:03:38,051 --> 00:03:41,748
<i>And Tiffany
He didn't have a pearl</i>

39
00:03:42,222 --> 00:03:45,214
<i>And Ziegfeld
Didn't even have a girl</i>

40
00:03:45,391 --> 00:03:48,883
<i>But anything can happen in New York</i>

41
00:03:49,062 --> 00:03:52,498
<i>You, too, can be that big ball of fire</i>

42
00:03:52,665 --> 00:03:55,964
<i>You, too, can have your name
In Who's Who</i>

43
00:03:56,135 --> 00:04:02,540
<i>You, too, can climb up higher and higher
Until you reach that Rainbow Room</i>

44
00:04:04,410 --> 00:04:08,141
<i>The Wall Street bankers
Didn't have a trust</i>

45
00:04:08,314 --> 00:04:12,011
<i>The Automat
It didn't have a crust</i>

46
00:04:12,185 --> 00:04:15,154
<i>The Hall Of Fame
It didn't have a bust</i>

47
00:04:15,321 --> 00:04:17,949
<i>But even you can be one in New York</i>

48
00:04:18,124 --> 00:04:22,493
<i>Yes, sir
You can be one in New York</i>

49
00:04:22,662 --> 00:04:25,859
<i>You, too, can be that big ball of fire</i>

50
00:04:26,032 --> 00:04:29,331
<i>You, too, can start from scratch
And get rich</i>

51
00:04:29,502 --> 00:04:32,869
<i>You, too, can climb up higher and higher</i>

52
00:04:33,039 --> 00:04:36,736
<i>Like Lord & Taylor, Bonwit Teller
Gimbel, Macy, Rockefeller</i>

53
00:04:36,909 --> 00:04:40,504
<i>You can even be an Abercrombie Fitch</i>

54
00:04:41,314 --> 00:04:44,943
<i>Once Mr. Morgan
Didn't have a yacht</i>

55
00:04:45,118 --> 00:04:48,918
<i>And Joe DiMaggio
Didn't have a swat</i>

56
00:04:49,088 --> 00:04:51,818
<i>The pot of gold
Didn't have a pot</i>

57
00:04:51,991 --> 00:04:56,018
<i>But anything can happen in New
Don't mean innuendo</i>

58
00:04:56,195 --> 00:05:02,100
<i>We mean only in New York</i>

59
00:05:02,568 --> 00:05:06,299
Yes, sir! Hey, hey, hey!

60
00:05:06,472 --> 00:05:09,464
That's the show! Hey, hey!

61
00:05:09,642 --> 00:05:14,511
Hey, that's us. Feed the little kitty, folks.
We take anything.

62
00:05:14,681 --> 00:05:16,774
Hey, all the way.

63
00:05:21,421 --> 00:05:24,322
Well, Nick, you got the armored car
outside for us tonight?

64
00:05:24,490 --> 00:05:27,084
- Boys, I've got bad news for you.
- What's the matter?

65
00:05:27,260 --> 00:05:29,228
I want you to resign.

66
00:05:29,395 --> 00:05:31,488
You mean,
you want us to quit working here?

67
00:05:31,664 --> 00:05:33,757
Oh, no, sir, Nick. We love you too much.

68
00:05:33,933 --> 00:05:37,528
We wouldn't let you sit in this cellar
all by yourself every night, would we?

69
00:05:37,704 --> 00:05:38,966
Then I got to fire you.

70
00:05:39,138 --> 00:05:41,470
- Fired?
- Why?

71
00:05:41,641 --> 00:05:44,542
Look, I got the business, yes?

72
00:05:44,711 --> 00:05:46,645
I got the wife, I got the three kids...

73
00:05:46,813 --> 00:05:49,407
...I got myself, I got you, yes?
- Yeah.

74
00:05:49,582 --> 00:05:52,915
But I only got three customers
eating my spaghetti.

75
00:05:53,086 --> 00:05:56,146
So, I've got to go out of business.

76
00:05:56,322 --> 00:05:58,722
That's too bad, Nick.

77
00:06:03,162 --> 00:06:07,098
Don't worry, Nick.
Spaghetti will come back someday.

78
00:06:12,071 --> 00:06:13,834
Hey, what's this? Five bucks.

79
00:06:14,006 --> 00:06:15,974
Wait a minute.
Who put this money in there?

80
00:06:16,142 --> 00:06:17,131
- Five dollars?
- Yeah.

81
00:06:17,310 --> 00:06:19,574
It couldn't be that icky from Waterbury,
could it?

82
00:06:19,746 --> 00:06:22,180
I don't get it.
She probably thought it was a buck.

83
00:06:22,348 --> 00:06:23,872
I'll have to give it back to her.

84
00:06:24,050 --> 00:06:28,077
Hey, you're not gonna cast that nice,
fresh folding money back on the waters.

85
00:06:28,254 --> 00:06:30,722
I hate to do it, fellas,
but things aren't that tough.

86
00:06:30,890 --> 00:06:34,087
And I better do it quick,
before my stomach talks to my willpower.

87
00:06:34,260 --> 00:06:37,195
Hey, wait a minute. Just let me hold it.

88
00:06:39,065 --> 00:06:41,158
Goodbye, Mr. Lincoln.

89
00:06:46,005 --> 00:06:48,303
Excuse me, lady,
but I think you made a mistake.

90
00:06:48,474 --> 00:06:51,443
- I found that in the kitty over there.
- Anything wrong with it?

91
00:06:51,611 --> 00:06:55,513
- It's a 5.
- The kitty says you take anything.

92
00:06:56,315 --> 00:06:57,543
You mean?

93
00:06:57,717 --> 00:07:00,743
Gosh, that's an awful lot of admission
just to watch us...

94
00:07:00,920 --> 00:07:03,514
...when you can see the top shows
on Broadway for $4.40.

95
00:07:03,689 --> 00:07:06,453
I think your show is as good
as some I've seen on Broadway.

96
00:07:06,626 --> 00:07:08,218
You do? You do?

97
00:07:08,394 --> 00:07:11,727
Oh, gosh, thanks.
We kind of think we're pretty good too.

98
00:07:11,898 --> 00:07:14,298
The straw hats around here
won't even listen to us...

99
00:07:14,467 --> 00:07:17,265
...and the out-of-town trade
very seldom gets down this way.

100
00:07:17,437 --> 00:07:19,564
Where are you from?
What part of the country?

101
00:07:19,739 --> 00:07:22,037
- I was born in Wisconsin, but l...
- Wisconsin?

102
00:07:22,208 --> 00:07:24,438
Well, that's funny.
My mom was born in Wisconsin.

103
00:07:24,610 --> 00:07:26,908
- You like New York?
- I get tired of it sometimes...

104
00:07:27,079 --> 00:07:28,740
Wait til you start swinging out.

105
00:07:28,915 --> 00:07:31,008
You know something?
You talk just like my mom.

106
00:07:31,184 --> 00:07:32,811
She said that God made New York...

107
00:07:32,985 --> 00:07:35,613
...just so that the good people
would enjoy Wisconsin.

108
00:07:35,788 --> 00:07:37,881
Your mother
might have something there.

109
00:07:38,057 --> 00:07:40,651
No place like it.
That's what I tell her in every letter.

110
00:07:40,827 --> 00:07:43,591
Where else can a fellow
shoot out of a firetrap like this...

111
00:07:43,763 --> 00:07:45,924
...into a top spot on Broadway?

112
00:07:46,098 --> 00:07:49,226
Sure, it happens every day.
Fellow comes in, sees something he likes.

113
00:07:49,402 --> 00:07:51,597
Says, "That's it."
Your name goes up in lights.

114
00:07:51,771 --> 00:07:53,238
- You're a hit overnight.
- Really?

115
00:07:53,406 --> 00:07:57,206
- Sort of like Horatio Alger, isn't it?
- Yeah, yeah.

116
00:07:57,777 --> 00:08:01,611
Only it hasn't happened to us
like that yet.

117
00:08:01,781 --> 00:08:04,648
The roof caved in on us tonight.
This bin's gonna close up.

118
00:08:04,817 --> 00:08:06,045
But we're on the upbeat.

119
00:08:06,219 --> 00:08:09,620
When we become headliners, we'll send
you tickets, get your money's worth.

120
00:08:09,789 --> 00:08:13,190
- You do that. I'll give you my address.
- Swell.

121
00:08:13,359 --> 00:08:15,452
- There.
- Well, thank you very much.

122
00:08:15,628 --> 00:08:18,290
Miss Jones from Wisconsin.

123
00:08:18,598 --> 00:08:20,964
You've been darn swell to us.

124
00:08:21,133 --> 00:08:24,660
If you need a couple of fellows to
show you the city or anything like that...

125
00:08:24,837 --> 00:08:27,738
Well, here, I'll give you one of our cards.
There you are.

126
00:08:34,347 --> 00:08:36,542
Which of the Three Balls of Fire are you?

127
00:08:37,049 --> 00:08:39,745
I'm the one you can't get any insurance on.
Tommy Williams.

128
00:08:39,919 --> 00:08:42,888
You can phone me at Pitt-Astor Drugstore.
I'm there all the time.

129
00:08:43,055 --> 00:08:47,492
It's kind of like an actors' clearing-house.
I'd like to show it to you sometime.

130
00:08:48,060 --> 00:08:49,584
That's very nice, Tommy.

131
00:08:49,762 --> 00:08:52,629
- I'm much obliged.
- Why, not at all.

132
00:08:52,798 --> 00:08:55,892
You liked our act, didn't you?
You give a fella a lot of heart.

133
00:08:56,068 --> 00:09:00,630
You know, the last person that made me
feel this good was my mother.

134
00:09:01,474 --> 00:09:04,375
That's a nicer compliment than I paid you.
You'll hear from me.

135
00:09:04,544 --> 00:09:07,308
You just drop your hat
and I'll come running.

136
00:09:07,480 --> 00:09:09,414
Oh, and thanks again for this fiver.

137
00:09:09,582 --> 00:09:12,142
You know, you made Santa Claus
seem like a schoolboy.

138
00:09:12,318 --> 00:09:17,119
It won't seem so much when you split it
three ways and deduct the income tax.

139
00:09:17,290 --> 00:09:19,258
- Goodbye.
- Goodbye.

140
00:09:30,002 --> 00:09:31,401
- Hello.
- Hello.

141
00:09:31,571 --> 00:09:33,505
- Hi, Tommy, Hammy.
- Hi, ladies.

142
00:09:33,673 --> 00:09:35,641
- Tommy, I got that part.
- Swell, Sally.

143
00:09:35,808 --> 00:09:37,036
- Wonderful.
- Great.

144
00:09:37,209 --> 00:09:39,609
- Hi, sexy boy.
- Oh, hello, fellas.

145
00:09:39,779 --> 00:09:41,610
- Been making the rounds?
- And how.

146
00:09:41,781 --> 00:09:43,772
- Anything new?
- Yeah, did you have any luck?

147
00:09:43,950 --> 00:09:46,441
I saw 14 producers,
but nobody's producing.

148
00:09:46,619 --> 00:09:48,883
<i>Oh, dear. That's...</i>

149
00:09:50,856 --> 00:09:54,587
Hi, Bert. Keep those sidewalks
hot enough nowadays, don't they?

150
00:09:54,760 --> 00:09:57,354
- Stop looking at that 85c dinner.
- Boys, what will it be?

151
00:09:57,530 --> 00:09:59,054
- Steak, medium.
- Chicken, fried.

152
00:09:59,231 --> 00:10:00,596
- Squab, broiled.
- Yeah, I know.

153
00:10:00,766 --> 00:10:03,701
- Three hams on rye and heavy on the ham.
- Oh, that's very funny.

154
00:10:03,869 --> 00:10:05,894
- There was a call for you guys.
- Call for us?

155
00:10:06,072 --> 00:10:09,633
- Yeah, the Thornton Reed office.
- Thornton Reed's office.

156
00:10:10,142 --> 00:10:11,837
- Thornton Reed?
- Easy, buddy.

157
00:10:12,011 --> 00:10:13,876
Don't you think it's too warm for jokes?

158
00:10:14,046 --> 00:10:17,504
I don't know, but she says Thornton Reed
Productions wants you before 6:00.

159
00:10:17,683 --> 00:10:20,345
How can we lose? We've been turned down
by every producer.

160
00:10:20,519 --> 00:10:25,013
Look here, Shorty, if this is a gag,
you've seen your last banana split.

161
00:10:40,706 --> 00:10:42,833
Hey, excuse me, ma'am.

162
00:10:43,009 --> 00:10:47,708
This may sound crazy to you,
but did you call us?

163
00:10:48,414 --> 00:10:49,972
Well, who are you?

164
00:10:51,384 --> 00:10:57,948
Well, we're the Three...

165
00:10:58,124 --> 00:11:00,490
- Balls of Fire.
- Balls of Fire.

166
00:11:02,061 --> 00:11:03,289
Right in there, please.

167
00:11:10,970 --> 00:11:14,098
Well, go ahead. It's only a doorknob.

168
00:11:21,781 --> 00:11:23,578
Well, hello.

169
00:11:24,750 --> 00:11:29,483
But, miss, I thought that you were...

170
00:11:29,655 --> 00:11:32,556
In Wisconsin?
I'm afraid not, not for 20 years.

171
00:11:32,725 --> 00:11:37,822
- But, Miss Jones, l...
- Hey, you're not Jonesy?

172
00:11:37,997 --> 00:11:40,932
<i>Not the famous Jo... Holy...</i>

173
00:11:41,934 --> 00:11:43,595
Well, aren't you going to sit down?

174
00:11:44,003 --> 00:11:45,630
Oh, yeah.

175
00:11:46,972 --> 00:11:49,236
And I was gonna show you New York.

176
00:11:49,675 --> 00:11:52,610
Maybe you will someday.
You know, I've never really seen it all.

177
00:11:52,778 --> 00:11:54,439
Now, boys, to get down to business.

178
00:11:54,613 --> 00:11:56,877
Mr. Reed is producing
a new musical revue.

179
00:11:57,049 --> 00:11:58,516
I have spoken to him about you.

180
00:11:58,684 --> 00:12:00,379
- About us?
- Thornton Reed?

181
00:12:00,553 --> 00:12:02,680
<i>This is getting to be like
Alice in Wonderland.</i>

182
00:12:02,855 --> 00:12:05,915
So if you'll be at the old Amsterdam
tomorrow morning at 11:00...

183
00:12:06,092 --> 00:12:08,185
...I may be able to get him
to watch your act.

184
00:12:08,360 --> 00:12:10,055
But please, you mustn't tell a soul.

185
00:12:10,229 --> 00:12:14,029
This is a very private audition.
Mr. Reed doesn't like actors.

186
00:12:16,435 --> 00:12:18,027
Well, do you think you can make it?

187
00:12:18,204 --> 00:12:21,332
- Make it?
- Right now, we've been there for hours.

188
00:12:21,507 --> 00:12:23,737
Hello. Oh, yes, Thornton.

189
00:12:23,909 --> 00:12:26,673
See you tomorrow morning
at the theater.

190
00:12:28,013 --> 00:12:30,140
- Thank you very much.
- Yes, Thornton.

191
00:12:30,316 --> 00:12:31,783
You don't know what you've done.

192
00:12:31,951 --> 00:12:33,384
What did you say, Thornton?

193
00:12:33,552 --> 00:12:37,886
I mean, what did you say, Thornton?
Oh, I don't know.

194
00:12:39,158 --> 00:12:41,388
I don't see any objection to Philadelphia.

195
00:12:42,461 --> 00:12:44,827
Read that, please. Read that.

196
00:12:44,997 --> 00:12:48,160
- Thanks very much. Goodbye.
- Bye.

197
00:12:50,102 --> 00:12:53,071
Sorry. Come on.

198
00:13:11,791 --> 00:13:13,156
- Hammy.
- Hiya, Jenny.

199
00:13:13,325 --> 00:13:15,452
You look as if you swallowed
the Academy Award.

200
00:13:15,628 --> 00:13:16,856
I'm really riding.

201
00:13:17,029 --> 00:13:20,590
Thornton Reed has just asked us
to come over to a little audition tomorrow...

202
00:13:20,766 --> 00:13:22,825
...at the old Amsterdam.
- Thornton Reed?

203
00:13:23,002 --> 00:13:25,300
Listen, you better come over.
You never can tell.

204
00:13:25,471 --> 00:13:28,269
- Thanks. That's one I owe you.
- But you better keep it quiet.

205
00:13:28,440 --> 00:13:30,635
- Don't forget kids, 11:00 sharp.
- Thanks, Tommy.

206
00:13:30,810 --> 00:13:33,904
That's all right. Shorty, remember those
ham sandwiches we ordered?

207
00:13:34,079 --> 00:13:35,512
Trade them in for top sirloins.

208
00:13:35,681 --> 00:13:38,479
- How do you want them?
- On a plate with a lot of potatoes.

209
00:13:38,651 --> 00:13:42,109
I'm not kidding. Tomorrow at the old
Amsterdam. Don't forget to tell Eddie.

210
00:13:42,288 --> 00:13:43,778
Keep this under your hats, kids.

211
00:13:43,956 --> 00:13:46,550
Thornton Reed's new musical,
the old Amsterdam, tomorrow.

212
00:13:46,725 --> 00:13:48,022
Actors working, yeah!

213
00:13:48,360 --> 00:13:50,954
Wait a minute, Shorty.
That's kind of quick, isn't it?

214
00:13:51,130 --> 00:13:54,566
- Pitt-Astor's super service.
- What did you do, send out for it?

215
00:13:56,135 --> 00:13:59,127
This is what I've been telling you
fellas about, eating acting.

216
00:13:59,305 --> 00:14:01,273
- Yes.
- Yeah.

217
00:14:04,977 --> 00:14:06,638
What's that?

218
00:14:12,384 --> 00:14:14,818
Excuse me, I'll be back in a minute.

219
00:14:19,925 --> 00:14:22,894
- Hey, you can't do that.
- Go away.

220
00:14:24,763 --> 00:14:28,859
- What are you crying about?
- None of your business.

221
00:14:40,412 --> 00:14:44,678
All right, come on, come on, break it up.
You've gotten your laugh.

222
00:14:44,850 --> 00:14:46,408
I don't think I like you.

223
00:14:46,585 --> 00:14:48,018
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

224
00:14:48,187 --> 00:14:50,417
- Now that we know each other...
- But we don't.

225
00:14:50,589 --> 00:14:52,853
My name is Williams, Tommy Williams.
What's yours?

226
00:14:54,260 --> 00:15:00,529
It doesn't matter. I'm just a failure.

227
00:15:00,699 --> 00:15:03,725
Oh, well, I was a failure yesterday.
Now look at me today.

228
00:15:05,437 --> 00:15:07,769
You mean,
you even looked worse yesterday?

229
00:15:11,377 --> 00:15:13,868
I'm sorry, I didn't mean that.

230
00:15:14,280 --> 00:15:18,216
But I was a success yesterday.

231
00:15:18,384 --> 00:15:21,615
You mean,
you even looked better yesterday?

232
00:15:25,324 --> 00:15:29,954
Oh, I worked and I slaved.

233
00:15:30,496 --> 00:15:36,628
There were only three words in the part,
but, oh, they were such beautiful words.

234
00:15:36,802 --> 00:15:38,326
"I love you"?

235
00:15:38,904 --> 00:15:40,462
No.

236
00:15:44,877 --> 00:15:47,744
"The telephone, madam."

237
00:15:50,115 --> 00:15:52,606
I never got past "the telephone."

238
00:15:54,086 --> 00:15:57,613
I just haven't got any talent.

239
00:15:59,758 --> 00:16:02,818
Well, you cry awfully pretty.

240
00:16:04,964 --> 00:16:08,559
- You think so?
- Yeah, no question.

241
00:16:08,734 --> 00:16:11,134
And I wouldn't worry
about three tired little words.

242
00:16:11,303 --> 00:16:13,430
You have talent.
Why, you're steaming with it.

243
00:16:13,605 --> 00:16:14,936
It's coming out all over you.

244
00:16:15,941 --> 00:16:18,603
And don't say you can't act,
because you can act.

245
00:16:18,777 --> 00:16:21,712
You're not unhappy,
you're only making yourself believe you are.

246
00:16:21,880 --> 00:16:25,611
And that's acting.
And that's why it's wonderful.

247
00:16:26,318 --> 00:16:28,878
You mean I don't really feel badly at all?

248
00:16:29,054 --> 00:16:31,545
Oh, of course, you do.
Of course, you do. Excuse me.

249
00:16:31,724 --> 00:16:35,216
But those are 14-karat tears
and you don't wanna waste them...

250
00:16:35,394 --> 00:16:39,524
...because someday, they'll come in awfully
handy at the curtain of the second act.

251
00:16:41,633 --> 00:16:44,329
But don't you have to feel better
to be able...?

252
00:16:44,503 --> 00:16:46,971
Sure you do,
but you don't want to let them touch you.

253
00:16:47,139 --> 00:16:51,098
Why, I'll bet right at this minute
you have more talent than Katharine Cornell.

254
00:16:51,276 --> 00:16:54,040
I'll bet at this minute
I've got more talent than Barrymore.

255
00:16:54,213 --> 00:16:56,738
That's what you've got
to keep dreaming and thinking.

256
00:16:56,915 --> 00:17:00,681
And when things get so bad
that you just wanna holler murder...

257
00:17:00,853 --> 00:17:03,185
...that's when you sell yourself
a bill of goods.

258
00:17:03,355 --> 00:17:06,256
And if you can do it then,
you can sell anybody.

259
00:17:12,131 --> 00:17:15,066
I guess I'm getting to be
quite a speechmaker.

260
00:17:15,801 --> 00:17:19,760
You know,
you don't talk like an actor at all.

261
00:17:19,938 --> 00:17:24,500
Oh, but I act like one.
You're through with that?

262
00:17:24,676 --> 00:17:26,701
- Oh, yeah, here.
- Thanks.

263
00:17:26,879 --> 00:17:30,906
Well, now that I've straightened
your life out, what's your name?

264
00:17:31,183 --> 00:17:34,277
- Penny.
- Penny, just like that?

265
00:17:34,453 --> 00:17:36,978
- No puns.
- All right, one-cent.

266
00:17:37,156 --> 00:17:39,624
- Where do you live?
- I live down that way.

267
00:17:39,792 --> 00:17:45,287
- Would a nickel swing it?
- No, but two might.

268
00:17:45,464 --> 00:17:47,489
All right, I'm declaring myself a partner.

269
00:17:47,666 --> 00:17:50,260
- Come on.
- All right.

270
00:17:53,205 --> 00:17:57,073
- Hey, where you going?
- I'm gonna fly this little sparrow home.

271
00:17:57,242 --> 00:18:01,702
Well, stay out of the stratosphere,
Cock Robin. We've got an act to rehearse.

272
00:18:05,517 --> 00:18:08,145
- You live far from the subway?
- I practically live in it.

273
00:18:08,320 --> 00:18:09,617
- Hiya, Mary.
- Hello, Penny.

274
00:18:09,788 --> 00:18:11,949
- Hello, Johnny. How's your mother?
- Much better.

275
00:18:12,124 --> 00:18:13,591
- Thanks for the cake.
- Okay.

276
00:18:13,759 --> 00:18:15,852
Well, here we are.

277
00:18:16,028 --> 00:18:19,293
- How are you on steps?
- Terrific.

278
00:18:34,880 --> 00:18:36,780
Hello, Papa. Papa.

279
00:18:36,949 --> 00:18:39,474
Oh, hello, dear. Oh, hello, hello.

280
00:18:39,651 --> 00:18:41,642
- Papa, this is Mr. Williams.
- How do you do?

281
00:18:41,820 --> 00:18:44,846
- How do you do? I hope we didn't interrupt.
- No, not at all.

282
00:18:45,023 --> 00:18:46,490
Barbara Jo is late again.

283
00:18:46,658 --> 00:18:49,058
Penny, if she comes,
you tell her she's a bad girl.

284
00:18:49,228 --> 00:18:53,665
You know, every time I have an orchestra
rehearsal for those children, why, I'm late.

285
00:18:53,832 --> 00:18:57,165
- Goodbye, young man. Glad to know you.
- Bye-bye, sir.

286
00:18:57,336 --> 00:18:59,668
- Oh, my.
- I hope I didn't drive him out.

287
00:18:59,838 --> 00:19:03,239
He was just afraid I was gonna ask him
if he collected from Mrs. Mulligan.

288
00:19:03,408 --> 00:19:05,569
He just won't ask for money.

289
00:19:06,145 --> 00:19:09,342
Boy, I'll bet this piano has played
a lot of empty stomach music.

290
00:19:09,515 --> 00:19:12,279
Yeah. Would you like a piece of cake?

291
00:19:12,451 --> 00:19:15,420
- Cake? Did you bake it?
- No, but I bought it.

292
00:19:15,587 --> 00:19:18,215
- Oh, bring it on then.
- All right.

293
00:19:24,796 --> 00:19:27,230
Where's Papa Morris? I'm late.

294
00:19:27,399 --> 00:19:29,629
Well, excuse me.
Are you taking a lesson?

295
00:19:29,801 --> 00:19:32,395
No, no, I'm just tuning the piano.

296
00:19:32,571 --> 00:19:34,562
You mean I won't be able
to take a lesson?

297
00:19:34,740 --> 00:19:38,141
You certainly won't. Where've you been?
This is the third time in a row...

298
00:19:38,310 --> 00:19:40,278
- It's wonderful, wait till you hear.
- What?

299
00:19:40,445 --> 00:19:43,107
They got the thing passed.
We're all going to the country.

300
00:19:43,282 --> 00:19:45,182
Two weeks, for free.
Isn't that marvelous?

301
00:19:45,350 --> 00:19:47,318
- All the kids?
- The whole settlement house.

302
00:19:47,486 --> 00:19:50,455
Mr. Stone just told me.
And I'm president of the whole thing.

303
00:19:50,622 --> 00:19:53,819
- Congratulations.
- This is Barbara Jo. This is Mr. Williams.

304
00:19:53,992 --> 00:19:57,484
- Pleased to meet you, Mr. Williams.
- Mr. Williams is an actor, you know.

305
00:19:57,663 --> 00:20:02,032
<i>- A real actor? On the stage?
- Well, I...</i>

306
00:20:02,201 --> 00:20:04,328
Here's your cake. Here, Barbara Jo.

307
00:20:04,503 --> 00:20:08,098
Gee, you don't look like an actor.

308
00:20:09,141 --> 00:20:11,735
That's what most of the producers think.

309
00:20:11,977 --> 00:20:14,537
- Won't you sit down, Mr. Williams?
- Thank you.

310
00:20:16,048 --> 00:20:20,109
You know, Mr. Williams, there's a couple
of things I don't understand about acting.

311
00:20:23,055 --> 00:20:24,716
Only a couple of things?

312
00:20:25,123 --> 00:20:26,385
When you're on the stage...

313
00:20:26,558 --> 00:20:28,651
...you have your arms around the girl
and say:

314
00:20:28,827 --> 00:20:31,591
"I love you more than
anything in the whole world."

315
00:20:31,763 --> 00:20:33,094
- Yeah?
- Do you really mean it?

316
00:20:33,265 --> 00:20:37,759
Well, that depends upon the girl.

317
00:20:38,904 --> 00:20:40,201
Yeah, I suppose so.

318
00:20:41,406 --> 00:20:45,809
But, gee, when Robert Taylor says it,
he makes me believe it.

319
00:20:45,978 --> 00:20:49,436
You know, Penny's gonna be an actress.
She's always acting.

320
00:20:49,615 --> 00:20:53,073
- Eat your cake, darling.
- Well, I am eating it.

321
00:20:55,687 --> 00:20:58,656
Oh, well, got to be going.
Big meeting tonight.

322
00:20:58,824 --> 00:21:01,088
Wait until the kids
find out they're really going.

323
00:21:01,260 --> 00:21:03,125
Some of them
never even seen the country.

324
00:21:03,295 --> 00:21:06,560
- Tell Papa I couldn't help it.
- I'll tell him, but you better practice.

325
00:21:06,732 --> 00:21:09,132
Why, Penny, you know I love to practice.

326
00:21:09,301 --> 00:21:12,134
Goodbye, Mr. Williams.
Sure like to see you act sometime.

327
00:21:12,304 --> 00:21:13,737
Well, thank you.

328
00:21:13,905 --> 00:21:15,463
Bye, Penny.

329
00:21:24,082 --> 00:21:25,709
- Won't you sit?
- Won't you sit?

330
00:21:30,389 --> 00:21:33,756
Here we are, just as if we had planned it.

331
00:21:33,925 --> 00:21:36,485
Yeah, you mean just as if we didn't.

332
00:21:40,499 --> 00:21:46,131
You know, I have a feeling that you're
gonna be that unknown quantity in my life.

333
00:21:46,305 --> 00:21:47,897
What's that?

334
00:21:49,174 --> 00:21:51,142
Something
that brings a fellow good luck.

335
00:21:51,310 --> 00:21:55,542
The springboard. The inspiration.

336
00:21:56,181 --> 00:21:59,275
The thing that everything adds up to.

337
00:21:59,451 --> 00:22:02,511
Gee, that's quite an assignment.

338
00:22:05,157 --> 00:22:07,387
Not with what you have.

339
00:22:08,460 --> 00:22:11,088
Just what have I, Mr. Williams?

340
00:22:11,263 --> 00:22:14,232
Well, it's a combination.

341
00:22:14,399 --> 00:22:19,564
A combination of something sweet
and warm.

342
00:22:22,107 --> 00:22:26,806
Plus a quality
that's far away from everybody.

343
00:22:26,978 --> 00:22:30,345
Reflection of talent, that's what it is.

344
00:22:31,216 --> 00:22:35,243
There's something special
lighting everything around you.

345
00:22:35,420 --> 00:22:39,516
- I didn't know I had that.
- Sure, that's what you have.

346
00:22:39,691 --> 00:22:41,625
And as soon as I see
Thornton tomorrow...

347
00:22:41,793 --> 00:22:44,455
...why, I'm gonna tell him
to take a good look at you.

348
00:22:44,629 --> 00:22:47,928
Before you know it, we'll be dancing
on top of the world, together.

349
00:22:48,100 --> 00:22:52,628
Oh, gee, that would be fun,
if it ever came true.

350
00:22:52,804 --> 00:22:54,863
As soon as I get through
with the audition...

351
00:22:55,040 --> 00:22:59,602
...why, I'll come back over here
and you'll see how true it is.

352
00:22:59,778 --> 00:23:01,507
Well, just so you won't get lost.

353
00:23:01,680 --> 00:23:03,910
I'll be at the settlement house
filing envelopes.

354
00:23:04,082 --> 00:23:07,813
And you can park your dream boat
right outside the entrance.

355
00:23:09,888 --> 00:23:13,847
- Now, will you do something for me?
- Lf I can.

356
00:23:14,025 --> 00:23:17,552
- Will you sing me a song?
- How do you know I can?

357
00:23:17,729 --> 00:23:22,223
Because you sing when you talk,
when you walk.

358
00:23:22,501 --> 00:23:25,265
Why, you're eyes are...
Why, they're singing right now.

359
00:23:26,638 --> 00:23:28,333
They are?

360
00:23:30,375 --> 00:23:32,468
Well, I'll be darned.

361
00:23:41,920 --> 00:23:47,859
<i>When a girl meets boy</i>

362
00:23:48,026 --> 00:23:54,488
<i>Life can be a joy</i>

363
00:23:54,666 --> 00:23:56,293
<i>But the note they end on</i>

364
00:23:56,468 --> 00:24:02,634
<i>Will depend on
Little pleasures they will share</i>

365
00:24:02,808 --> 00:24:09,304
<i>So let us compare</i>

366
00:24:11,183 --> 00:24:14,914
<i>I like New York in June</i>

367
00:24:15,086 --> 00:24:18,522
<i>How about you?</i>

368
00:24:18,690 --> 00:24:22,126
<i>I like a Gershwin tune</i>

369
00:24:22,294 --> 00:24:26,196
<i>How about you?</i>

370
00:24:26,364 --> 00:24:33,133
<i>I love a fireside
When a storm is due</i>

371
00:24:33,305 --> 00:24:37,036
<i>I like potato chips
Moonlight and motor trips</i>

372
00:24:37,209 --> 00:24:41,111
<i>How about you?</i>

373
00:24:41,279 --> 00:24:47,650
<i>I'm mad about good books
Can't get my fill</i>

374
00:24:47,819 --> 00:24:54,122
<i>And Franklin Roosevelt's looks
Give me a thrill</i>

375
00:24:54,292 --> 00:24:59,127
<i>Holding hands in the movie show
When all the lights are low</i>

376
00:24:59,297 --> 00:25:04,360
<i>May not be new
But I like it</i>

377
00:25:04,536 --> 00:25:10,133
<i>How about you?</i>

378
00:25:11,510 --> 00:25:14,809
<i>I like Jack Benny's jokes</i>

379
00:25:14,980 --> 00:25:18,108
<i>To a degree</i>

380
00:25:18,283 --> 00:25:21,741
<i>I love the common folks</i>

381
00:25:21,920 --> 00:25:25,117
<i>That includes me</i>

382
00:25:25,624 --> 00:25:32,120
<i>I like to window shop on 5th Avenue</i>

383
00:25:32,297 --> 00:25:35,824
<i>I like banana splits
Late supper at the Ritz</i>

384
00:25:36,001 --> 00:25:39,198
<i>How about you?</i>

385
00:25:39,371 --> 00:25:46,368
<i>I love to dream of fame
Maybe I'll shine</i>

386
00:25:46,545 --> 00:25:52,347
<i>I'd love to see your name
Right beside mine</i>

387
00:25:52,517 --> 00:25:55,145
<i>I can see we're in harmony</i>

388
00:25:55,320 --> 00:26:00,223
<i>Looks like we both agree
On what to do</i>

389
00:26:00,392 --> 00:26:02,519
<i>- And I like it
- And I like it</i>

390
00:26:02,694 --> 00:26:08,792
<i>- How about you?
- How about you?</i>

391
00:26:09,768 --> 00:26:12,999
<i>I'm so delighted
I've ignited the spark within you</i>

392
00:26:13,171 --> 00:26:16,629
<i>Let me continue to make it burn</i>

393
00:26:16,808 --> 00:26:20,005
<i>With you, I will be like a Trilby
So let's not dally</i>

394
00:26:20,178 --> 00:26:23,409
<i>Come on, Svengali
I've lots to learn</i>

395
00:26:23,582 --> 00:26:28,178
<i>When you're arising
Start exercising daily</i>

396
00:26:28,353 --> 00:26:30,287
<i>For example
Just a sample</i>

397
00:26:30,455 --> 00:26:33,652
<i>Bend and touch the floor
Fifty times or more</i>

398
00:26:33,825 --> 00:26:37,158
<i>A fine start
To be a Bernhardt</i>

399
00:26:37,329 --> 00:26:40,594
<i>A dictionary's necessary
But not for talking</i>

400
00:26:40,765 --> 00:26:43,791
<i>It's used for walking
The Ziegfeld way</i>

401
00:26:43,969 --> 00:26:47,598
<i>Is this okay?</i>

402
00:26:47,772 --> 00:26:51,037
<i>That's the trick
You're catching on quickly</i>

403
00:26:51,209 --> 00:26:52,540
<i>Should I take a bow?</i>

404
00:26:52,711 --> 00:26:54,372
<i>Oh, let me show you how</i>

405
00:26:54,546 --> 00:26:58,004
<i>- Just like partners on the stage
- Yeah.</i>

406
00:26:58,183 --> 00:27:03,951
<i>If you can use a partner
I'm the right age</i>

407
00:29:27,999 --> 00:29:29,694
Hey, don't go under there.

408
00:29:29,868 --> 00:29:32,666
The way our luck's been running,
I wish it was Friday the 13th.

409
00:29:32,837 --> 00:29:35,237
- Oh, no, you don't.
- Wait a minute, what's the idea?

410
00:29:35,406 --> 00:29:37,738
- This happens to be Friday.
- And the 13th.

411
00:29:37,909 --> 00:29:38,898
It is?

412
00:29:39,077 --> 00:29:40,476
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

413
00:29:41,279 --> 00:29:44,544
Strange. Well, here we are.
Remember, this Thornton Reed is big-league.

414
00:29:44,716 --> 00:29:47,116
This is a private audition.
No mugging, no pressing.

415
00:29:47,285 --> 00:29:49,048
- Don't look anxious.
- All right.

416
00:29:50,622 --> 00:29:54,183
Quiet! Quiet! Quiet!

417
00:29:55,026 --> 00:29:57,290
Look's like
somebody's been reading our mail.

418
00:29:57,462 --> 00:30:01,364
Easy, folks. Easy, folks. Do you realize
you're getting on Mr. Reed's nerves?

419
00:30:01,533 --> 00:30:04,593
Mason, where's the boy
with my sandwich?

420
00:30:04,769 --> 00:30:07,670
He'll be here.
I think he got lost in the crowd.

421
00:30:07,839 --> 00:30:11,172
- I can't even get a 10c sandwich.
- Thornton, remember your headache.

422
00:30:11,342 --> 00:30:14,072
Don't rub me down.
You're the cause of all this.

423
00:30:14,245 --> 00:30:17,043
You and your discoveries.
I don't want to discover anyone.

424
00:30:17,215 --> 00:30:19,683
I give you my word.
This time, I only told three boys.

425
00:30:19,851 --> 00:30:21,409
Where, in Yankee Stadium?

426
00:30:21,586 --> 00:30:24,384
This is wonderful.
Every actor in New York will love you.

427
00:30:24,556 --> 00:30:28,219
I don't want every actor in New York
to love me. I want my wife to love me.

428
00:30:28,393 --> 00:30:32,989
- Drink this.
- I don't want it, I want my sandwich. I'm...

429
00:30:33,164 --> 00:30:34,927
Mason, you've got to keep them back.

430
00:30:35,099 --> 00:30:37,260
- Please, please, please.
- I'm keeping them back.

431
00:30:37,435 --> 00:30:40,563
People, you must stop this nonsense.

432
00:30:40,738 --> 00:30:45,801
All I'm doing is a little intimate musical,
not the Passion play.

433
00:30:45,977 --> 00:30:50,539
- Quiet, quiet, quiet!
- Listen, we want to give everyone a chance.

434
00:30:50,715 --> 00:30:54,412
But unless you line up so I can see you,
I'll have to call the whole thing off.

435
00:30:55,119 --> 00:30:57,553
- Come on, Jenny. Let's get in.
- Get in, Helen.

436
00:30:57,722 --> 00:31:01,488
- Quit shoving back there, you pig.
- What's the big idea?

437
00:31:01,659 --> 00:31:05,060
Mr. Reed, you don't know us, but
we just closed the Tip-Top Inn in Albany.

438
00:31:05,230 --> 00:31:06,857
Yeah, we're the Four Hot Licks.

439
00:31:07,031 --> 00:31:08,020
- May...
- Ray...

440
00:31:08,199 --> 00:31:09,757
- Fay...
- And Kay.

441
00:31:09,934 --> 00:31:14,997
<i>Oh, sextet from Madam Lucia</i>

442
00:31:15,173 --> 00:31:18,802
<i>Oh, sextet
I love you, yeah</i>

443
00:31:18,977 --> 00:31:21,673
Please, please, some other time.

444
00:31:21,846 --> 00:31:25,111
Mason, have them pass by in one line
so we could get through with this.

445
00:31:25,283 --> 00:31:26,545
Mr. Reed will see you.

446
00:31:26,718 --> 00:31:28,845
- Keep in one line, keep moving.
- No, I'm sorry.

447
00:31:29,020 --> 00:31:30,954
- Make it snappy.
- Yes, I could use you.

448
00:31:31,122 --> 00:31:33,113
- Yes, no, too small.
- Just keep on going.

449
00:31:33,291 --> 00:31:35,555
- No, too short. No, boys.
- No.

450
00:31:35,727 --> 00:31:37,558
- What do you mean, no?
- But, Thornton...

451
00:31:37,729 --> 00:31:40,527
- I mean no, I can't use you.
- Well, how do you know?

452
00:31:40,698 --> 00:31:42,791
- How do l...?
- You haven't seen us do anything.

453
00:31:42,967 --> 00:31:46,334
We're the Three Balls of Fire.
Once we get started, you can't put us out.

454
00:31:46,504 --> 00:31:48,904
But I can put you out
before you get started. Mason.

455
00:31:49,073 --> 00:31:53,032
Thornton, wait. These are the boys I've
been telling you about. They're tremendous.

456
00:31:53,211 --> 00:31:55,441
In three years,
they'll be greater than Astaire.

457
00:31:55,613 --> 00:31:58,810
Then bring them back in three years.
I'm sorry, lad, some other time.

458
00:31:58,983 --> 00:32:01,144
- Not now, that's all. I'm sorry.
- Mr. Reed, l...

459
00:32:01,319 --> 00:32:02,650
All right, keep them going.

460
00:32:02,820 --> 00:32:05,015
- Just keep on going.
- No, no, no, I'm sorry.

461
00:32:05,189 --> 00:32:08,818
No, I can't use you.
No, no children. No, no children.

462
00:32:08,993 --> 00:32:12,656
Wait, wait,
don't send my brother to the chair.

463
00:32:12,830 --> 00:32:17,494
Don't let him burn.
Please, please, warden, please.

464
00:32:17,669 --> 00:32:21,400
Mr. Reed, I have some clippings here.
This is Maxine when she was a little girl...

465
00:32:21,572 --> 00:32:24,336
Mason, Mason.

466
00:32:25,143 --> 00:32:28,544
Maybe we ought to change our name
to the Three Puffs of Smoke.

467
00:32:28,713 --> 00:32:31,841
Private audition.
How do you like her, giving us that?

468
00:32:32,016 --> 00:32:35,918
It's not her fault.
It's those producers. They're all the same.

469
00:32:36,087 --> 00:32:41,525
Just send out nonchalantly for 1000 actors
every time they get lonesome.

470
00:32:41,859 --> 00:32:48,594
Well, I guess we're cooked, fellas.
Yep, on both sides.

471
00:32:48,766 --> 00:32:49,994
What do we do now, Tom?

472
00:32:50,168 --> 00:32:53,069
I've been pedaling that hocus-pocus
about talent and ambition.

473
00:32:53,237 --> 00:32:57,367
They don't want talent. They wouldn't know
talent if it was wrapped up in the mailbox.

474
00:32:57,542 --> 00:32:59,203
I guess it's back to the bulrushes.

475
00:32:59,377 --> 00:33:02,107
Maybe I don't belong in show business.
I don't know.

476
00:33:02,580 --> 00:33:06,710
It's all right, I'll do something else. Drive
a truck, dig ditches, sell shoes, anything.

477
00:33:06,884 --> 00:33:09,216
Take it easy, Tommy.
You know you're not serious.

478
00:33:09,387 --> 00:33:11,514
We'll be back
making the rounds again tomorrow.

479
00:33:11,689 --> 00:33:13,657
- Something will turn up.
- Not me, brother.

480
00:33:13,825 --> 00:33:16,225
What are you trying to do,
split up the axis?

481
00:33:16,394 --> 00:33:18,362
How long you gonna go
through life singing?

482
00:33:18,529 --> 00:33:21,191
How long are you gonna
keep yourself in hock to producers?

483
00:33:21,366 --> 00:33:23,334
Until you become a producer yourself.

484
00:33:23,501 --> 00:33:26,698
Until you become a producer yourself.
That's very funny.

485
00:33:26,871 --> 00:33:28,862
Until you become a producer yourself.

486
00:33:32,910 --> 00:33:37,244
Sure. Why not?

487
00:33:38,383 --> 00:33:40,851
There's nothing magic to it.

488
00:33:42,987 --> 00:33:47,924
All you need is a little courage,
taste, money.

489
00:33:48,092 --> 00:33:51,220
Yeah, and we're loaded
with courage and taste.

490
00:33:51,396 --> 00:33:55,127
We've got lots of talent.
So why don't we sign ourselves up?

491
00:33:55,299 --> 00:33:59,395
Four months ago, when we came to this
city, we devoted our lives to the theater.

492
00:33:59,570 --> 00:34:01,504
Here comes the Gettysburg Address.

493
00:34:01,672 --> 00:34:04,004
We got the brush
from the New York producers.

494
00:34:04,175 --> 00:34:05,403
Living or dead.

495
00:34:05,576 --> 00:34:08,409
We've got a satchel full of talent
and no place to display it.

496
00:34:08,579 --> 00:34:10,342
So we'll build our own showcase.

497
00:34:10,548 --> 00:34:14,609
- Have you forgotten about money?
- Or are you planning to win a raffle?

498
00:34:15,553 --> 00:34:18,215
Money? Well, anybody can
put on a show with money.

499
00:34:18,389 --> 00:34:20,084
Let's not be corny about this thing.

500
00:34:20,258 --> 00:34:23,352
Oh, certainly, can't be corny,
so let's forget about money.

501
00:34:23,528 --> 00:34:25,086
What do we use instead?

502
00:34:26,931 --> 00:34:31,061
<i>Well, anything. We can use...</i>

503
00:34:31,602 --> 00:34:37,939
Well, you know... like a... a cause.

504
00:34:39,710 --> 00:34:40,734
- A what?
- A what?

505
00:34:40,945 --> 00:34:42,469
A cause.

506
00:34:42,647 --> 00:34:48,051
A great, big beautiful cause.
Something that'll tug at their heartstrings...

507
00:34:48,219 --> 00:34:51,347
...make them dig down in their jeans
and bring tears to their eyes.

508
00:34:51,522 --> 00:34:53,114
You better stop eating that salami.

509
00:34:53,291 --> 00:34:55,384
Don't you realize that America
is cause-crazy?

510
00:34:55,560 --> 00:34:59,326
Why, they give shows for everybody.
China, the Red Cross, Bundles for Britain.

511
00:34:59,497 --> 00:35:01,863
There must be some place
they haven't thought of.

512
00:35:02,033 --> 00:35:03,762
Right here.

513
00:35:04,969 --> 00:35:06,561
Now you're talking.

514
00:35:06,737 --> 00:35:08,898
How about a cause for eatless actors?

515
00:35:09,073 --> 00:35:13,373
Actors? No, nobody cares about actors.
It's gotta be something solid.

516
00:35:13,544 --> 00:35:16,377
- Like widows, orphans, dogs.
- How about mailmen or motormen?

517
00:35:16,547 --> 00:35:19,072
- No, no, glamour.
- How about ball players?

518
00:35:19,250 --> 00:35:21,480
They've all got chicken farms.

519
00:35:21,652 --> 00:35:25,144
- Hey, I got it. I got it.
- Well, what is it?

520
00:35:25,323 --> 00:35:27,757
How about chorus girls?

521
00:35:28,893 --> 00:35:30,656
Well, how about them?

522
00:35:32,597 --> 00:35:38,035
I'm sorry, Hammy.
I guess I'm just blowing bubbles again.

523
00:35:38,636 --> 00:35:40,968
If only I hadn't written
that big buildup to Mom...

524
00:35:41,139 --> 00:35:43,801
...promised the city hall to everybody.

525
00:35:51,949 --> 00:35:53,712
Hey, where are you going?

526
00:35:53,885 --> 00:35:57,753
I'm gonna get a little air. I'm a little flat.

527
00:36:26,817 --> 00:36:28,751
What's your claim?

528
00:36:31,622 --> 00:36:35,581
Look, look,
things can't be as bad as all that.

529
00:36:36,127 --> 00:36:39,563
You don't know what happened.

530
00:36:40,097 --> 00:36:43,863
Something awful happened to me,
but I'm not crying, look.

531
00:36:44,035 --> 00:36:46,299
You're a boy.

532
00:36:48,639 --> 00:36:52,006
You know, you cry awfully pretty.

533
00:36:53,411 --> 00:36:57,609
- I do?
- Sure, you cry beautifully.

534
00:36:57,782 --> 00:37:01,946
Why, if I thought I looked that pretty,
I'd be crying my eyes out all the time.

535
00:37:02,119 --> 00:37:05,111
You know what?
I'm gonna make you my official crier.

536
00:37:07,191 --> 00:37:10,683
Well, and as soon as things get tough...

537
00:37:10,861 --> 00:37:13,591
...why, I'll give you the signal
and you can turn it on.

538
00:37:13,764 --> 00:37:17,825
Why, everybody can cry
if they're unhappy themselves.

539
00:37:18,002 --> 00:37:20,994
It's not me so much. I've seen it.

540
00:37:21,172 --> 00:37:25,905
But some of the other kids,
they never even been there.

541
00:37:26,077 --> 00:37:30,514
<i>- And those old trustees...
- The who?</i>

542
00:37:30,881 --> 00:37:32,371
The Board of Trustees.

543
00:37:32,550 --> 00:37:37,852
They promised we were going to the country
for two whole weeks.

544
00:37:38,022 --> 00:37:41,958
And now they tell us
they can't give us the money.

545
00:37:42,326 --> 00:37:46,786
Well, don't you worry about it.
You're still young.

546
00:37:46,964 --> 00:37:50,365
<i>You have lots of time to go to the...</i>

547
00:37:54,038 --> 00:37:58,031
Hey, what did you say?

548
00:38:00,444 --> 00:38:06,246
We were gonna see cows and brooks
and milk them and everything.

549
00:38:06,417 --> 00:38:09,352
You mean, they backed out on you?

550
00:38:10,688 --> 00:38:15,091
Why, I've never heard of such a thing.
Why, how dare they do that?

551
00:38:15,259 --> 00:38:18,456
- Come on, we'll go see about it right now.
- See about what?

552
00:38:18,629 --> 00:38:22,087
These kids have never seen the sunlight,
babbling brooks, blade of grass...

553
00:38:22,266 --> 00:38:24,166
...a bluebird flitting from tree to tree.

554
00:38:24,335 --> 00:38:27,236
What has happened to the milk
of human kindness? Where is he?

555
00:38:27,405 --> 00:38:29,930
- Where's who?
- The whatchamacallit, the number one guy.

556
00:38:30,107 --> 00:38:32,371
- The superintendent? He's inside.
- That's our man.

557
00:38:32,543 --> 00:38:34,773
<i>Why, the idea of these people,
these children...</i>

558
00:38:36,180 --> 00:38:39,115
So all you have to do is give us the word
and we're ready to go.

559
00:38:39,283 --> 00:38:40,682
I like your enthusiasm.

560
00:38:40,851 --> 00:38:43,285
I'm afraid it's a much bigger job
than you imagine.

561
00:38:43,454 --> 00:38:45,581
No, it isn't.
You see, Tommy's a professional.

562
00:38:45,756 --> 00:38:49,351
Yes, I know, but where are you
going to get all the talent?

563
00:38:50,494 --> 00:38:52,962
Talent?
Why, the world is riddled with talent.

564
00:38:53,130 --> 00:38:55,257
You can shake it out of trees.
It's right here.

565
00:38:55,433 --> 00:38:58,630
This girl right here, she's
the greatest singer of songs I ever heard.

566
00:38:58,803 --> 00:39:01,203
You've got the greatest crying act
in show business.

567
00:39:01,372 --> 00:39:02,964
<i>And as for myself, well...</i>

568
00:39:03,140 --> 00:39:06,576
And if that isn't enough, I can
walk into a drugstore on 44th street...

569
00:39:06,744 --> 00:39:09,474
...throw a rock, hit more talent
than on any Broadway show.

570
00:39:09,647 --> 00:39:11,842
Well, that takes care of the talent.

571
00:39:12,016 --> 00:39:14,484
Now, where do you propose
putting this show on?

572
00:39:14,652 --> 00:39:15,983
In the auditorium?

573
00:39:16,153 --> 00:39:18,621
They couldn't seat over
100 people there.

574
00:39:18,789 --> 00:39:22,020
No, this has gotta be big.
This isn't gonna be any amateur night.

575
00:39:22,193 --> 00:39:23,421
It's gotta be gigantic.

576
00:39:23,594 --> 00:39:26,961
Like the World Series or the Aquacade.
This is Rose Bowl stuff.

577
00:39:27,131 --> 00:39:29,463
Why, it looks as if
you'll need a whole city block.

578
00:39:29,633 --> 00:39:31,066
Yeah.

579
00:39:33,971 --> 00:39:38,965
City block. Yeah. Sure, that's it.
Right in the neighborhood.

580
00:39:39,143 --> 00:39:41,168
We'll rope it off.
Everybody will come to it.

581
00:39:41,345 --> 00:39:45,748
We give them a sample, then pass the hat.
With the money we take, we'll hire the hall.

582
00:39:45,916 --> 00:39:49,113
Put on a show for half a buck
that'll send those kids to the country.

583
00:39:49,286 --> 00:39:51,584
Well, I must admit
you have a wonderful platform.

584
00:39:51,756 --> 00:39:53,747
- Couldn't we, Mr. Stone?
- Please, please?

585
00:39:53,924 --> 00:39:57,451
Well, in the face of all this enthusiasm,
what can I say?

586
00:39:57,628 --> 00:40:02,065
But I'm not guaranteeing
that Mr. Busch will be swept off his feet.

587
00:40:02,233 --> 00:40:03,530
Mr. Busch? Who's Mr. Busch?

588
00:40:03,701 --> 00:40:08,570
The district leader. He's the only one
who can give you a permit for a block party.

589
00:40:08,739 --> 00:40:11,902
- Tough customer?
- A very tough customer.

590
00:40:12,710 --> 00:40:15,907
Come on, we'll go there, see if we
can cut him down to our size. Bye.

591
00:40:16,080 --> 00:40:17,809
- Thank you.
- That's quite all right.

592
00:40:19,917 --> 00:40:23,648
So here's this character sitting there,
Simon J. Busch.

593
00:40:23,821 --> 00:40:25,152
Typical ward heeler.

594
00:40:25,322 --> 00:40:29,156
Heater sticking out the side of his mouth,
big black derby with heart to match.

595
00:40:29,326 --> 00:40:31,817
So I go to work on him. I say:

596
00:40:31,996 --> 00:40:37,730
"Mr. Busch, if you donate this city block,
it'll send you to Congress."

597
00:40:37,902 --> 00:40:39,563
He keeps on smoking.

598
00:40:39,737 --> 00:40:44,299
I try to appeal to his sense of chivalry.
He can't even spell it.

599
00:40:44,475 --> 00:40:48,639
I talk to him about his school days.
He never went.

600
00:40:48,813 --> 00:40:51,475
Things are desperate
and Barbara Jo was crying so hard...

601
00:40:51,649 --> 00:40:54,447
...she looks like a road show edition
of the Johnstown flood.

602
00:40:54,618 --> 00:40:57,348
So I slide right into the theme song.

603
00:41:00,458 --> 00:41:03,450
"Mr. Busch, you're not gonna keep
these starving kiddies away...

604
00:41:03,627 --> 00:41:06,528
...from the babbling brooks,
and the birds that sing...

605
00:41:06,697 --> 00:41:09,188
...and the vitamins A, B, C, and D.

606
00:41:09,366 --> 00:41:13,234
You're not gonna be responsible
for young America growing up with rickets.

607
00:41:13,404 --> 00:41:15,998
Oh, no, not you, Mr. Busch.

608
00:41:16,173 --> 00:41:20,269
Not you. Not a man who reminds me
so much of Thomas Jefferson."

609
00:41:20,444 --> 00:41:22,344
Then I had tell him who Jefferson is.

610
00:41:22,513 --> 00:41:24,481
I tell you, he folded up
like a wet tent.

611
00:41:24,648 --> 00:41:27,378
He started to cry, tears came
as big as Ping-Pong balls.

612
00:41:27,551 --> 00:41:29,314
He just couldn't resist the cause.

613
00:41:29,487 --> 00:41:31,148
It's the sucker shot of the century.

614
00:41:31,322 --> 00:41:33,654
If we play our cards right,
use those kids right...

615
00:41:33,824 --> 00:41:37,760
...we'll land right in the middle of Broadway
with four-forty written all over us.

616
00:41:38,996 --> 00:41:43,456
And all the time, Mr. Busch just kept
sitting there, smoking that smelly old cigar.

617
00:41:43,634 --> 00:41:46,000
And just when I was sure
he was gonna say no...

618
00:41:46,170 --> 00:41:48,297
...Mr. Williams got right on top
of the desk...

619
00:41:48,472 --> 00:41:50,599
...and he told him
what wonderful kids we were.

620
00:41:50,774 --> 00:41:54,403
And if we didn't all get sunshine
and fresh air, we'd wind up with pickets.

621
00:41:54,578 --> 00:41:56,773
- With what?
- Pickets.

622
00:41:56,947 --> 00:41:58,244
Darling, you mean rickets.

623
00:41:58,415 --> 00:42:02,579
Well, anyway, he was wonderful,
and Mr. Busch finally said he'd go it.

624
00:42:02,753 --> 00:42:04,345
- And you know what, Penny?
- What?

625
00:42:04,522 --> 00:42:07,457
All I could think of was...

626
00:42:08,526 --> 00:42:12,860
...was Abraham Lincoln
freeing the slaves.

627
00:42:13,364 --> 00:42:14,956
I'm gonna tell him you said that.

628
00:42:15,132 --> 00:42:17,794
- He'll like that.
- Oh, I wish you would.

629
00:42:17,968 --> 00:42:20,801
- Gee, he's exceptional.
- Yeah.

630
00:42:20,971 --> 00:42:23,872
Too bad he isn't better-looking.

631
00:42:24,041 --> 00:42:29,069
Why, Barbara Jo, he's fine-looking.
He's got character in his face.

632
00:42:29,246 --> 00:42:33,182
You know he turned down an opportunity
in a Broadway show just to do this?

633
00:42:33,350 --> 00:42:34,783
- Honest?
- Yes.

634
00:42:34,952 --> 00:42:36,977
And you'll never know
what that meant to him.

635
00:42:37,154 --> 00:42:41,215
I couldn't have done it,
not even my three little words.

636
00:42:41,392 --> 00:42:46,227
Gosh, he never stops
to think of himself.

637
00:42:47,264 --> 00:42:48,595
But he'll be paid back.

638
00:42:50,334 --> 00:42:56,034
You know, Penny, if it was
anybody else but you, I'd be jealous.

639
00:42:58,075 --> 00:43:01,067
If it was anybody else but him,
you could have him.

640
00:43:24,635 --> 00:43:25,693
- Is it all right?
- Yeah.

641
00:43:25,869 --> 00:43:28,133
- Let's get it on the pole.
- Okay.

642
00:43:29,640 --> 00:43:30,834
- How's that?
- Swell, Tony.

643
00:43:31,008 --> 00:43:32,771
The tempo's perfect. Just right.

644
00:43:32,943 --> 00:43:34,911
I know my dance all right.
Can I go now?

645
00:43:35,079 --> 00:43:36,876
Sure, Ronnie. Sign your name over here.

646
00:43:37,047 --> 00:43:40,107
- I'll have to take the children.
- Right. Thank you, Mrs. Crainen.

647
00:43:40,284 --> 00:43:42,684
- Come on, children.
- Jenny, give me that.

648
00:43:42,853 --> 00:43:44,912
Everybody, can I have
your attention please?

649
00:43:45,089 --> 00:43:46,886
After you get through with your work...

650
00:43:47,057 --> 00:43:50,254
...whether painting a sign,
practicing a song or dance, you can leave.

651
00:43:50,427 --> 00:43:53,089
Other performers are coming in.
They have to rehearse too.

652
00:43:53,263 --> 00:43:57,063
After your work, sign one of these cards
before you go out. Thanks, everybody.

653
00:43:57,234 --> 00:43:59,828
Oh, Penny, get your costume on.
We're gonna do our skit.

654
00:44:00,004 --> 00:44:02,097
- All right.
- Will you come and see my costume?

655
00:44:02,272 --> 00:44:03,466
I have no time now.

656
00:45:07,971 --> 00:45:11,304
All right, everybody,
let's have it quiet, please, quiet now!

657
00:45:11,475 --> 00:45:13,966
Everybody, take those signs
and banners and posters...

658
00:45:14,144 --> 00:45:15,611
...and put them in the anteroom.

659
00:45:15,779 --> 00:45:18,179
Move that piano here in this corner.
Hurry up, now!

660
00:45:18,348 --> 00:45:21,181
All the rest of you,
come on down here by the stand here.

661
00:45:21,351 --> 00:45:23,216
Come on, right up close to the platform.

662
00:45:23,387 --> 00:45:25,947
That's it. Now let me have
your attention please! Quiet!

663
00:45:26,123 --> 00:45:30,287
Now, look, we're gonna do the number first,
so all of you get in your aprons and overalls.

664
00:45:30,461 --> 00:45:33,555
Come on, now, let's move.
And don't forget, give us lots of zambo.

665
00:45:33,731 --> 00:45:35,358
Go ahead, take it, Johnny.

666
00:45:49,813 --> 00:45:54,614
<i>When our grandmas and our grandpas
Were just girls and boys</i>

667
00:45:54,785 --> 00:45:59,313
<i>They seemed to have
A lot more fun than we</i>

668
00:46:00,557 --> 00:46:05,824
<i>Their party clothes were calicoes
And homemade corduroys</i>

669
00:46:05,996 --> 00:46:11,263
<i>And a big event
Was called a husking bee</i>

670
00:46:11,435 --> 00:46:15,337
<i>A banjo and a fiddle
And a big old-fashioned barn</i>

671
00:46:15,506 --> 00:46:19,067
<i>Was all the preparation that they made</i>

