01:06:05,928 --> 01:06:08,863
We got $42 last night
and with your contribution, it makes 67.

889
01:06:09,031 --> 01:06:11,864
All we need is a theater.
You find out about the old Duchess?

890
01:06:12,034 --> 01:06:13,763
Yes, and Mr. Reed still owns it.

891
01:06:13,936 --> 01:06:16,871
But I'm afraid it won't be any good
to you, Tommy.

892
01:06:17,039 --> 01:06:19,530
- Why not?
- Well, it hasn't been occupied in years.

893
01:06:19,709 --> 01:06:21,540
Hasn't even any seats in it.

894
01:06:21,711 --> 01:06:23,508
Well, it has a stage, hasn't it?

895
01:06:23,679 --> 01:06:26,375
Yes, but it's a warehouse.

896
01:06:26,549 --> 01:06:30,041
Oh, we don't care. We'll take it.
Here, I got the bread right with me. Here.

897
01:06:30,219 --> 01:06:32,915
- Sixty-seven dollars.
- No, Tommy. I'd have to ask Mr. Reed.

898
01:06:33,089 --> 01:06:36,718
And I can't bother him now.
He's having so much trouble.

899
01:06:36,892 --> 01:06:40,191
Hello? Oh, hello, Marelli.
Did you get them?

900
01:06:40,796 --> 01:06:45,631
But Mr. Reed will give them 1500
and feature billing.

901
01:06:46,135 --> 01:06:49,332
All right, Marelli. Yes, I know you tried.
Thank you.

902
01:06:51,340 --> 01:06:53,865
Don't see why he wouldn't let us
have it for one night.

903
01:06:54,043 --> 01:06:55,408
We'd fix it up and everything.

904
01:06:55,978 --> 01:06:59,607
The Duchess? No, no, Tommy.
That's completely out of the question.

905
01:06:59,782 --> 01:07:04,549
Poor Thornton.
I don't know what I'm going to do.

906
01:07:05,187 --> 01:07:07,747
Look, you don't happen
to know of an act...

907
01:07:07,923 --> 01:07:12,519
...a good group that could be spotted
a couple of times in Mr. Reed's show?

908
01:07:12,695 --> 01:07:14,424
- Sure, I do.
- Who? Where?

909
01:07:14,597 --> 01:07:18,158
- Right here. The Three Balls of Fire.
- No, no, Tommy, I need a big act.

910
01:07:18,334 --> 01:07:21,167
Twelve, 15 people, and a singer.

911
01:07:21,337 --> 01:07:24,397
What about our group and Penny?
How about the act we did yesterday?

912
01:07:24,573 --> 01:07:27,508
- It stopped traffic. You said so yourself.
- I wonder...

913
01:07:27,676 --> 01:07:31,407
<i>No, no, no. Thornton wouldn't...</i>

914
01:07:32,148 --> 01:07:35,015
I don't know why not, though.

915
01:07:35,584 --> 01:07:39,645
Look, could you get that wonderful girl?
What's her name?

916
01:07:39,822 --> 01:07:41,915
- Penny. Penny Morris?
- Yes, could you get her?

917
01:07:42,091 --> 01:07:44,889
Your gang from the drugstore.
Get them together and rehearse.

918
01:07:45,061 --> 01:07:48,997
Do the number tomorrow afternoon at
a matinee exactly as you did it last night.

919
01:07:49,165 --> 01:07:52,657
You mean that? You mean?
You mean it? We're gonna...?!

920
01:07:52,835 --> 01:07:57,135
Yes, for Mr. Reed's show tomorrow
in Philadelphia.

921
01:07:57,306 --> 01:07:59,740
Tomorrow. Sure, why not?

922
01:07:59,909 --> 01:08:02,844
All right. Get them all together.
Be here in my office at 5:00.

923
01:08:03,012 --> 01:08:08,109
We're taking the 6:00 train for Philadelphia,
and may heaven have mercy on my soul.

924
01:08:08,284 --> 01:08:13,984
Six o'clock, 5:00.
We'll be here. Okay!

925
01:08:14,957 --> 01:08:17,755
All aboard for Philadelphia!

926
01:08:21,997 --> 01:08:24,693
Don't move! Stay where you are!
Stop me if I sound crazy...

927
01:08:24,867 --> 01:08:29,099
...but tonight, you, me, and all the kids from
the drugstore are leaving on the train...

928
01:08:29,271 --> 01:08:32,502
...and tomorrow in Philadelphia,
we open in Thornton Reed's new show!

929
01:08:36,145 --> 01:08:38,670
You think I'm crazy, but I'm not.
We're going tonight.

930
01:08:38,848 --> 01:08:41,681
No luck, eh? Hallelujah.
Truth will out, talent will tell!

931
01:08:41,851 --> 01:08:43,284
- Now, wait...?
- I can see it now.

932
01:08:43,452 --> 01:08:47,013
Tommy Williams, Penny Morris,
the Balls of Fire in lights as big as coconuts!

933
01:08:47,189 --> 01:08:51,285
Success! Success, in three easy lessons.
Now what do you think of Williams?

934
01:08:52,027 --> 01:08:54,860
- I think Williams is still Williams.
- What?!

935
01:08:55,030 --> 01:08:57,362
You're going to Philadelphia?
Without me, because...

936
01:08:57,533 --> 01:09:00,991
Without you? Penny, are you crazy?
This is it. What are you talking about?

937
01:09:01,170 --> 01:09:03,468
The same thing.
Those little kids we promised...

938
01:09:03,639 --> 01:09:05,800
That was before.
Thornton Reed, he's in trouble.

939
01:09:05,975 --> 01:09:08,375
If we can save this show,
we can land our own ticket.

940
01:09:08,544 --> 01:09:10,944
What about Hammy, Ray,
all the kids at the drugstore?

941
01:09:11,113 --> 01:09:13,343
They waited all their lives
for a shot like this.

942
01:09:13,516 --> 01:09:15,040
But Reed's got a million dollars.

943
01:09:15,217 --> 01:09:18,948
And you and I and Hammy and Ray
can hang on till we get another chance.

944
01:09:19,121 --> 01:09:22,579
- But, gosh, those little kids...
- No.

945
01:09:22,758 --> 01:09:23,986
Oh, Tommy, don't you see?

946
01:09:24,160 --> 01:09:26,958
It's not the two weeks in the country
that's gonna cure them.

947
01:09:27,129 --> 01:09:29,359
It's giving a kid something
he's dreamed about...

948
01:09:29,532 --> 01:09:32,797
...so maybe he won't feel like
there's nothing left to go on for later.

949
01:09:32,968 --> 01:09:36,028
Gosh, I wanna go to Philadelphia
just as much as you do.

950
01:09:36,205 --> 01:09:40,198
But if I did it, it would be just like stealing
their stockings off the Christmas tree.

951
01:09:40,376 --> 01:09:42,367
I can't do that. I just can't, that's all.

952
01:09:42,545 --> 01:09:44,012
You don't get the point at all.

953
01:09:44,180 --> 01:09:47,240
I'm talking about the lives and careers
of 15 people. Artists.

954
01:09:47,416 --> 01:09:50,476
I'm talking about Tommy Williams
and Penny Morris, the performers.

955
01:09:50,653 --> 01:09:53,213
That has nothing to do with kids
getting to the country.

956
01:09:53,389 --> 01:09:55,414
Let's get to be stars first
and then we can...

957
01:09:55,591 --> 01:09:58,492
Never mind, don't bother.
You haven't heard anything I've said.

958
01:09:58,661 --> 01:10:01,858
- Don't make me do anything I regret...
- Go on! Go to Philadelphia!

959
01:10:02,031 --> 01:10:03,589
I hope you stop the show!

960
01:10:03,766 --> 01:10:06,360
Well, all right, then.

961
01:10:08,771 --> 01:10:11,296
I'll get it fixed!

962
01:10:12,908 --> 01:10:17,572
Mr. Williams! Mr. Williams! Mr. Williams,
I've been looking for you all morning...

963
01:10:17,746 --> 01:10:20,579
- I'm sorry, I'm awfully busy.
- Please, it's awfully important.

964
01:10:20,749 --> 01:10:22,717
Everybody's waiting in the auditorium.

965
01:10:22,885 --> 01:10:25,217
Well, all right, hurry up,
I've got an appointment.

966
01:10:25,387 --> 01:10:27,184
Thanks a lot. It'll only take a minute.

967
01:10:32,361 --> 01:10:34,124
Hey, what's this all about?

968
01:10:35,864 --> 01:10:37,126
- What do you want?
- Come on.

969
01:10:37,299 --> 01:10:39,699
- Look, here he comes! Here he comes!
- Here he comes!

970
01:10:39,868 --> 01:10:41,699
- Yeah.
- Come on!

971
01:10:49,645 --> 01:10:52,614
Well, Mr. Williams,
all the kids and myself...

972
01:10:52,781 --> 01:10:55,011
...we had a meeting
of the executive committee...

973
01:10:55,184 --> 01:10:58,244
...and we were talking about how you
gave up a big Broadway show...

974
01:10:58,420 --> 01:11:02,584
...to do all this for us
and we weren't doing anything for you.

975
01:11:02,758 --> 01:11:05,192
Well, that's not right.

976
01:11:05,361 --> 01:11:08,922
There's been a lot of talk around this place
about getting us to the country.

977
01:11:09,098 --> 01:11:12,727
But nobody ever did anything about it
except you.

978
01:11:12,901 --> 01:11:16,667
You just walked right in
and didn't listen to anybody.

979
01:11:16,839 --> 01:11:22,368
And now we're going.
After all the promises, we're really going.

980
01:11:22,578 --> 01:11:28,107
Well, well, we just wanna say thank you.

981
01:11:28,284 --> 01:11:31,344
But with 50 kids to do it,
it would take an awful long time.

982
01:11:31,520 --> 01:11:33,010
We know you're a busy man.

983
01:11:33,188 --> 01:11:40,185
So we all chipped in and
bought you a present, and here it is.

984
01:12:00,115 --> 01:12:04,347
You shouldn't have.
You shouldn't have done this, because l...

985
01:12:04,520 --> 01:12:06,181
Don't you like it?

986
01:12:06,355 --> 01:12:09,051
Sure, sure I like it.

987
01:12:10,292 --> 01:12:17,130
It's swell. In fact, it's one of
the nicest presents I've ever seen.

988
01:12:17,900 --> 01:12:21,859
You shouldn't have spent the money
on me, though.

989
01:12:22,471 --> 01:12:26,635
But I'm glad you did,
because every time I look at this watch...

990
01:12:28,377 --> 01:12:30,368
...l'm gonna see every one of your faces...

991
01:12:30,546 --> 01:12:34,243
...and gonna remember
what a swell gang you are.

992
01:12:35,918 --> 01:12:39,479
Honest, you'll never know
what it means to me.

993
01:12:39,655 --> 01:12:45,616
All I can say is that
I haven't even started to earn it.

994
01:12:45,794 --> 01:12:47,625
But I will.

995
01:12:48,030 --> 01:12:50,260
And after it's all over with
and all through...

996
01:12:50,432 --> 01:12:54,994
...I hope that you'll be glad
that you gave it to me.

997
01:12:56,138 --> 01:12:58,368
And you don't have to worry
about the country...

998
01:12:58,540 --> 01:13:04,638
...because you're not only going,
but you're gonna go first class too.

999
01:13:16,024 --> 01:13:18,254
Penny. Penny.

1000
01:13:18,961 --> 01:13:21,088
- Hello, Mr. Stone.
- How do you do?

1001
01:13:24,400 --> 01:13:26,425
Oh, excuse me. Is Penny here?

1002
01:13:26,602 --> 01:13:29,799
- I think she's up on the roof.
- Oh, thanks.

1003
01:13:42,584 --> 01:13:43,812
<i>Penny...</i>

1004
01:13:43,986 --> 01:13:46,682
You better hurry.
You're gonna miss that train.

1005
01:13:47,489 --> 01:13:51,152
I just have one more speech to make
and I have to make it.

1006
01:13:53,829 --> 01:13:55,922
You don't have to listen
if you don't want to.

1007
01:13:56,098 --> 01:13:58,293
Go ahead, I'm listening.

1008
01:14:01,837 --> 01:14:04,533
All my life, I've been rehearsing myself
to be a big man...

1009
01:14:04,706 --> 01:14:08,335
...and it's taken me just five minutes
to find out that I'm only a heel.

1010
01:14:08,877 --> 01:14:11,402
Bunch of little kids chip in
their nickels and dimes...

1011
01:14:11,580 --> 01:14:16,244
...to buy me a $5 watch
marked down to 3.50. There it is.

1012
01:14:17,019 --> 01:14:20,113
And I'm so ashamed at myself
that it took a bunch of 6-year-olds...

1013
01:14:20,289 --> 01:14:25,090
...to make me realize that there's more to
life than just a song, a dance and an encore.

1014
01:14:25,694 --> 01:14:30,427
And that there's more to people than just
sitting out front, being an audience.

1015
01:14:32,534 --> 01:14:37,062
Well, it's half past 1
and that's the end of my speech.

1016
01:14:37,239 --> 01:14:40,800
Oh, Tommy, that's a wonderful speech.

1017
01:14:42,744 --> 01:14:45,679
And life begins at half past 1.

1018
01:14:50,953 --> 01:14:55,219
Penny, I've got a couple of words
I wanna say to you...

1019
01:14:55,958 --> 01:14:58,654
...just this time, sitting down.

1020
01:15:00,762 --> 01:15:02,662
Only a couple?

1021
01:15:03,232 --> 01:15:06,099
Well, really three.

1022
01:15:07,302 --> 01:15:10,601
Well, go ahead and say them
and get them over with.

1023
01:15:13,208 --> 01:15:17,508
Oh, I could say "I love you"
just like all the rest of them.

1024
01:15:18,614 --> 01:15:20,878
That's still good, you know.

1025
01:15:21,049 --> 01:15:23,882
But it wouldn't tell you
what I really mean.

1026
01:15:24,486 --> 01:15:25,919
I'll settle for it.

1027
01:15:26,088 --> 01:15:29,421
Oh, no, you're not gonna talk me
out of my love scene.

1028
01:15:35,864 --> 01:15:37,297
Were you ever in a rainstorm...

1029
01:15:37,466 --> 01:15:41,300
...and you felt like you were the only person
in the world that wasn't getting wet?

1030
01:15:41,470 --> 01:15:43,734
Did you ever look up
and see a full moon and...

1031
01:15:43,906 --> 01:15:46,306
...well, it only looked like
a half a moon to you...

1032
01:15:46,475 --> 01:15:48,500
...because you were
looking at it all alone?

1033
01:15:49,578 --> 01:15:52,411
Penny, did you ever find someone and...

1034
01:15:53,615 --> 01:15:59,520
...and all of a sudden, you felt like
you were taking off, right out into space...

1035
01:15:59,688 --> 01:16:05,593
...like a propeller going round and round
and round, 30,000 revolutions a minute...

1036
01:16:05,761 --> 01:16:09,026
...and there wasn't any landing fields
left in the world?

1037
01:16:10,699 --> 01:16:13,224
I've had that feeling.

1038
01:16:13,402 --> 01:16:16,371
And it all started in a drugstore.

1039
01:16:19,074 --> 01:16:22,475
- Penny.
- Yeah?

1040
01:16:25,447 --> 01:16:26,846
Tommy.

1041
01:16:27,015 --> 01:16:30,678
Oh, isn't it wonderful what you can find
these days in drugstores?

1042
01:16:30,852 --> 01:16:32,945
- Yeah.
- Oh, gosh.

1043
01:16:37,893 --> 01:16:40,987
And that's about all there is to it.

1044
01:16:42,230 --> 01:16:49,227
I know, it even sounds crazy to me,
but that's the way it has to be.

1045
01:16:50,305 --> 01:16:53,502
Well, I guess I'll have to send
these railroad tickets back, then.

1046
01:16:54,776 --> 01:16:59,213
Gee, I hate to have you do that.

1047
01:17:00,082 --> 01:17:02,550
- Maybe if l...
- Tommy.

1048
01:17:04,553 --> 01:17:07,021
I hope you don't think we're ungrateful,
Miss Jones...

1049
01:17:07,189 --> 01:17:09,953
...because you've
been simply wonderful...

1050
01:17:10,525 --> 01:17:14,291
...but this is the way Tommy and I
have decided to do it.

1051
01:17:14,463 --> 01:17:16,431
Isn't it, Tommy?

1052
01:17:16,898 --> 01:17:22,336
Yeah, yeah, that's what we've decided.

1053
01:17:23,338 --> 01:17:27,138
You're giving up this great opportunity
to help a bunch of kids you hardly know.

1054
01:17:30,345 --> 01:17:32,905
Helping people's hard work, isn't it?

1055
01:17:33,081 --> 01:17:34,309
Don't you worry.

1056
01:17:34,483 --> 01:17:39,819
You'll find it's worthwhile at
the oddest times and the strangest places.

1057
01:17:43,392 --> 01:17:45,292
How soon can you get
your show together?

1058
01:17:47,629 --> 01:17:51,258
Our show? Oh, in about 10 days.

1059
01:17:51,433 --> 01:17:53,958
Yeah, our only problem
is getting a theater.

1060
01:17:54,136 --> 01:17:57,333
Well, there's no problem now.

1061
01:17:58,206 --> 01:18:01,232
- You mean we can have the old Duchess?
- Yes.

1062
01:18:01,410 --> 01:18:04,174
No, put your bread away.
If the theater's any good to you...

1063
01:18:04,346 --> 01:18:07,179
...you can have it as
Thornton's contribution to the cause.

1064
01:18:07,983 --> 01:18:09,416
He doesn't even have to know.

1065
01:18:09,584 --> 01:18:12,849
It's on Gilmore Street, about seven
blocks from the settlement house.

1066
01:18:13,021 --> 01:18:15,717
- How about that?
- It's wonderful, I don't know what to say.

1067
01:18:15,891 --> 01:18:17,188
Don't say anything.

1068
01:18:17,359 --> 01:18:19,623
Just get your show started
and make it good.

1069
01:18:19,795 --> 01:18:22,992
Thornton doesn't know it,
and he won't until I'm ready to tell him...

1070
01:18:23,165 --> 01:18:26,225
...but he's gonna see your show
in his theater from the front row.

1071
01:18:26,401 --> 01:18:28,062
- Oh, you see, Tommy?
- Yeah.

1072
01:18:28,236 --> 01:18:30,898
But Miss Jones,
won't Mr. Reed be angry?

1073
01:18:31,073 --> 01:18:33,667
Very likely.
That's why it's got to be good.

1074
01:18:33,842 --> 01:18:38,074
Otherwise, I'll find myself in the country
with the rest of the kids.

1075
01:19:33,435 --> 01:19:37,269
Gosh. Isn't it beautiful?

1076
01:19:38,907 --> 01:19:41,432
It's kind of run-down, isn't it?

1077
01:19:43,345 --> 01:19:45,176
It's wonderful.

1078
01:19:46,047 --> 01:19:49,881
Well, maybe after we clean it up
and brighten it a little...

1079
01:19:50,051 --> 01:19:54,215
...but right now,
it's giving me the creeps.

1080
01:19:54,389 --> 01:19:58,951
- It does?
- It's kind of like a haunted house.

1081
01:19:59,628 --> 01:20:02,620
Penny, every theater is a haunted house.

1082
01:20:03,799 --> 01:20:05,323
Ghosts with greasepaint...

1083
01:20:05,500 --> 01:20:09,095
...ghosts that sing and dance
and laugh and cry.

1084
01:20:09,838 --> 01:20:13,740
You should think of all the shows
that have been in this theatre.

1085
01:20:14,609 --> 01:20:20,479
Flops, successes, bad shows,
great shows.

1086
01:20:21,550 --> 01:20:24,383
You can't tell me that that ever dies.

1087
01:20:24,553 --> 01:20:30,514
It's all around us right now,
all the laughter and applause, cheers.

1088
01:20:31,259 --> 01:20:34,626
Why, it's on every inch
of this old stage up here.

1089
01:20:35,664 --> 01:20:39,395
- Do you see what I mean?
- Yeah, I see what you mean.

1090
01:20:39,568 --> 01:20:41,832
Then when new ones come along,
kids like us...

1091
01:20:42,003 --> 01:20:44,437
...that love the theatre
just as much as they did...

1092
01:20:44,606 --> 01:20:47,370
...they're glad and they're rooting for us.

1093
01:20:47,542 --> 01:20:51,103
They're saying, "This is your chance.

1094
01:20:51,279 --> 01:20:55,113
Go on out there, we've had ours,
now it's your turn.

1095
01:20:55,283 --> 01:20:57,808
There's your audience.
They're waiting for you."

1096
01:20:59,521 --> 01:21:02,081
Can't you just see it now?

1097
01:21:04,259 --> 01:21:05,954
Look.

1098
01:21:06,561 --> 01:21:10,827
The leader taps his stand with his stick.
The music starts.

1099
01:21:10,999 --> 01:21:13,365
The footlights gradually come up.

1100
01:21:13,535 --> 01:21:17,904
This is that one breathless moment when
everything in the world comes to a stop.

1101
01:21:18,406 --> 01:21:21,807
Over in the wings, the light man
at the board reaches for the switch.

1102
01:21:21,977 --> 01:21:26,107
Now the hands that pull the curtain
are on the rope, waiting for the cue.

1103
01:21:26,281 --> 01:21:29,182
The curtain rises slowly.

1104
01:21:29,918 --> 01:21:34,150
I never saw them, but I feel as though
I'd been here watching them every night.

1105
01:21:34,623 --> 01:21:37,888
<i>Richard Mansfield in Cyrano de Bergerac.</i>

1106
01:21:38,059 --> 01:21:41,790
I know just how he felt,
standing there, waiting for his cue.

1107
01:21:44,065 --> 01:21:47,364
Your nose is rather large.

1108
01:21:48,036 --> 01:21:52,029
- Have you quite finished, sir?
- I should say that is sufficient.

1109
01:21:52,207 --> 01:21:54,300
You humdrum dolt.

1110
01:21:54,476 --> 01:21:58,742
How dare you insult a splendid nose
with such meager, piddling words?

1111
01:21:58,914 --> 01:22:02,077
Let me show you what you might
have said had you had an ounce...

1112
01:22:02,250 --> 01:22:05,219
...yes, even an ounce of imagination
or wit.

1113
01:22:05,387 --> 01:22:08,288
To wit, insolent.

1114
01:22:09,190 --> 01:22:11,181
What do you do with that nose
when drinking?

1115
01:22:11,359 --> 01:22:15,125
Does it go above the glass or below
the glass, for surely, it does not fit inside.

1116
01:22:15,297 --> 01:22:18,528
Descriptive. It's a rock.

1117
01:22:19,601 --> 01:22:23,093
It's a mountain.
What am I saying, a mountain?

1118
01:22:24,673 --> 01:22:28,734
It's a peninsula. Eloquent.

1119
01:22:28,910 --> 01:22:35,577
What is that dazzling thing, sir?
Is it a torch? A bonfire? A volcano?

1120
01:22:35,750 --> 01:22:37,684
Stamp it out before it blinds my eyes.

1121
01:22:37,852 --> 01:22:42,414
- Buffoon.
- Who, me?

1122
01:22:43,058 --> 01:22:45,185
So be it.

1123
01:22:46,294 --> 01:22:50,355
Prepare to die exquisitely.

1124
01:22:50,532 --> 01:22:52,693
- Poet.
- Yes, poet.

1125
01:22:52,867 --> 01:22:58,237
Swordsman, take your choice.
No, wait. You shall have both.

1126
01:22:58,406 --> 01:23:02,638
For while I fight with you,
I shall compose a ballad...

1127
01:23:02,811 --> 01:23:09,717
...and with the last line of my poem,
my sword shall run you through.

1128
01:23:09,918 --> 01:23:12,751
<i>Swiftly, my hat is tossed aside.</i>

1129
01:23:12,921 --> 01:23:15,583
<i>Slowly, my cloak is allowed to fall
over my left free arm.</i>

1130
01:23:15,757 --> 01:23:18,658
<i>And to draw and we stand on guard.</i>

1131
01:23:18,827 --> 01:23:24,356
<i>Lunge, and my sword is met with yours.
Dancers of steel that dazzle the eye.</i>

1132
01:23:24,532 --> 01:23:26,762
<i>Back you go, in time to my verse.</i>

1133
01:23:26,935 --> 01:23:30,666
<i>And then, when I have finished my song,
you die.</i>

1134
01:23:30,839 --> 01:23:34,104
<i>Pray now, while you still have life.</i>

1135
01:23:34,275 --> 01:23:36,835
<i>Prince, pray, with your final sigh.</i>

1136
01:23:37,012 --> 01:23:39,947
<i>Stay, look sharp, I've run out of verse.</i>

1137
01:23:40,115 --> 01:23:47,078
<i>And now, as I finish my song,
you die</i>

1138
01:24:02,137 --> 01:24:07,700
<i>For it is Mary, Mary</i>

1139
01:24:07,876 --> 01:24:11,812
<i>Plain as any name can be</i>

1140
01:24:11,980 --> 01:24:14,972
<i>But with propriety</i>

1141
01:24:15,150 --> 01:24:21,282
<i>Society will say "Marie"</i>

1142
01:24:21,456 --> 01:24:26,587
<i>But it was Mary, Mary</i>

1143
01:24:26,761 --> 01:24:30,561
<i>Long before the fashions came</i>

1144
01:24:30,732 --> 01:24:37,604
<i>And there is something there
That sounds so square</i>

1145
01:24:37,772 --> 01:24:42,471
<i>It's a grand old name</i>

1146
01:24:42,644 --> 01:24:47,843
<i>But it was Mary, Mary</i>

1147
01:24:48,016 --> 01:24:52,146
<i>Long before the fashions came</i>

1148
01:24:52,320 --> 01:24:56,120
<i>And there is something there</i>

1149
01:24:56,291 --> 01:25:00,057
<i>That sounds so square</i>

1150
01:25:00,228 --> 01:25:06,656
<i>It's a grand old name</i>

1151
01:25:14,776 --> 01:25:20,146
<i>For she's my Daisy</i>

1152
01:25:20,315 --> 01:25:23,250
<i>My bonnie Daisy</i>

1153
01:25:24,018 --> 01:25:26,384
<i>She's as sweet as sugar candy</i>

1154
01:25:26,554 --> 01:25:28,988
<i>And she's very fond of Sandy</i>

1155
01:25:29,157 --> 01:25:35,619
<i>And I worry for my dearie</i>

1156
01:25:35,797 --> 01:25:41,929
<i>I would rather lose my kilt
Than lose my Daisy</i>

1157
01:25:47,675 --> 01:25:54,171
<i>For I would rather lose my kilt
Than lose my Daisy</i>

1158
01:26:01,756 --> 01:26:06,557
<i>Sure, I've got rings on my fingers
And bells on my toes</i>

1159
01:26:06,728 --> 01:26:10,664
<i>Elephants to ride upon
My little Irish rose</i>

1160
01:26:10,832 --> 01:26:14,393
<i>So come to your nabob
On next Patrick's Day</i>

1161
01:26:14,569 --> 01:26:18,061
<i>Be Mistress Mumbo-Jumbo
Jij-Ji-Bo J. O'Shea</i>

1162
01:26:18,239 --> 01:26:23,108
<i>Sure, I've got rings on my fingers
And bells on my toes</i>

1163
01:26:23,278 --> 01:26:26,907
<i>Elephants to ride upon
My little Irish rose</i>

1164
01:26:27,081 --> 01:26:30,812
<i>So come to your nabob
On next Patrick's Day</i>

1165
01:26:30,985 --> 01:26:37,447
<i>Be Mistress Mumbo-Jumbo
Jij-Ji-Bo J. O'Shea</i>

1166
01:27:33,147 --> 01:27:39,643
<i>I'm a Yankee Doodle Dandy
Yankee Doodle do or die</i>

1167
01:27:39,954 --> 01:27:46,450
<i>A real live nephew of my Uncle Sam
I was born on the 4th of July</i>

1168
01:27:46,828 --> 01:27:53,324
<i>I've got a Yankee Doodle sweetheart
She's my Yankee Doodle joy</i>

1169
01:27:54,335 --> 01:27:57,600
<i>Yankee Doodle came to London
Just to ride the ponies</i>

1170
01:27:57,772 --> 01:28:01,208
<i>Say, I am a Yankee Doodle Boy</i>

1171
01:28:01,576 --> 01:28:08,072
<i>He's a Yankee Doodle Dandy
A Yankee Doodle do or die</i>

1172
01:28:08,416 --> 01:28:14,912
<i>A real live nephew of his Uncle Sam
Born on the 4th of July</i>

1173
01:28:15,356 --> 01:28:19,315
<i>I've got a Yankee Doodle sweetheart</i>

1174
01:28:19,494 --> 01:28:22,657
<i>She's my Yankee Doodle joy</i>

1175
01:28:23,131 --> 01:28:26,658
<i>Yankee Doodle came to London
Just to ride the ponies</i>

1176
01:28:26,834 --> 01:28:32,636
<i>I am a Yankee Doodle boy</i>

1177
01:29:39,107 --> 01:29:42,508
- Come in.
- Oh, Tommy, they're beautiful.

1178
01:29:42,677 --> 01:29:45,942
- Maybe I should have got a dozen more.
- No, one would have been enough.

1179
01:29:46,114 --> 01:29:49,083
Once, you told me I was
gonna be dancing on top of the world...

1180
01:29:49,250 --> 01:29:53,880
...and tonight, I'm all filled up with things
I've been saving to say...

1181
01:29:54,055 --> 01:29:57,718
...but now that the time is here,
I guess I'll just go on and say them, huh?

1182
01:29:57,892 --> 01:30:00,793
But, Tommy... oh, no, don't go.
I want to thank you too.

1183
01:30:00,962 --> 01:30:03,453
You've done so much and...

1184
01:30:03,631 --> 01:30:06,099
...I guess I'll never be happier
than I am tonight.

1185
01:30:06,968 --> 01:30:12,497
- Hey, Tommy, your mother's here.
- Oh, Mom! How are you?

1186
01:30:12,673 --> 01:30:15,938
Wait a minute. What are you doing,
working your way through college?

1187
01:30:16,110 --> 01:30:18,908
I bought them all on the train.
I was saving them for you.

1188
01:30:19,080 --> 01:30:21,378
You've grown a little, haven't you?

1189
01:30:21,549 --> 01:30:23,744
Mom, I'd like you
to meet some of my friends.

1190
01:30:23,918 --> 01:30:27,615
No, no, no. Don't tell me.
This is Penny, of course.

1191
01:30:27,789 --> 01:30:30,553
I'm awful glad to meet you.
How'd you know it was me?

1192
01:30:30,725 --> 01:30:34,024
Tommy writes
such wonderful descriptions.

1193
01:30:34,195 --> 01:30:38,188
- And of course, this is Hammy.
- No, Mom, that's Ray.

1194
01:30:38,366 --> 01:30:40,334
In back of you, that's Hammy.

1195
01:30:40,501 --> 01:30:44,198
- Of course, the one with the blank verse.
- That's him.

1196
01:30:44,372 --> 01:30:46,067
- Fifteen minutes.
- I've got to go.

1197
01:30:46,240 --> 01:30:50,233
Excuse me. I'll see you after the show.
And here. This is for recognizing me.

1198
01:30:50,411 --> 01:30:53,175
You go on out and get your seat now.
See you after the show.

1199
01:30:53,347 --> 01:30:55,144
You come back, if you'll talk to me.

1200
01:30:55,316 --> 01:30:59,616
Here it is, son, this wonderful minute,
just as we talked about it so many times.

1201
01:30:59,787 --> 01:31:02,381
Yeah, sort of jumped up
on top of us, huh?

1202
01:31:02,557 --> 01:31:05,856
Yes, and the funniest thing is
I'm not the least bit nervous.

1203
01:31:06,027 --> 01:31:08,791
No, no, of course, you're not.
Of course, you're not. Here.

1204
01:31:08,963 --> 01:31:10,624
Give me a kiss for good luck, huh?

1205
01:31:10,798 --> 01:31:12,060
- You got your tickets?
- Yes.

1206
01:31:12,233 --> 01:31:14,497
- I'll see you after the show. Bye.
- All right.

1207
01:31:14,669 --> 01:31:16,603
Gosh, what a peach of a mom, huh?

1208
01:31:16,771 --> 01:31:20,400
- I wish Jonesy and Reed would get here.
- Don't worry, Jonesy won't let us down.

1209
01:31:20,575 --> 01:31:22,600
- You think he'll go for us?
- He'll go for us.

1210
01:31:22,777 --> 01:31:24,870
I hope they don't leave
before our big number.

1211
01:31:25,046 --> 01:31:29,005
With Jonesy on one side and mom on the
other, I'm taking the short end of the bet.

1212
01:31:29,183 --> 01:31:31,151
- Ten minutes.
- Hey, we'd better hurry.

1213
01:31:31,319 --> 01:31:34,311
I'm gonna go out front and
see the house, huh? Be right back.

1214
01:31:35,756 --> 01:31:40,250
- Mr. Williams, how do I look?
- You look swell, Barbara Jo.

1215
01:31:40,428 --> 01:31:42,589
- Good luck to you.
- Thanks.

1216
01:31:46,634 --> 01:31:51,401
Tommy Williams. My boy.
Acting since he was that high.

1217
01:31:53,007 --> 01:31:54,235
- Tommy. Hey, Tommy.
- Yeah?

1218
01:31:54,408 --> 01:31:58,037
- She's here. Jones.
- Oh, swell. Excuse me, Maria.

1219
01:31:58,212 --> 01:32:00,840
Jonesy, am I glad to see you.
Where is he?

1220
01:32:01,015 --> 01:32:02,676
- He's not here, Tommy.
- Not here?

1221
01:32:02,850 --> 01:32:04,283
I'm terribly sorry, Tommy.

1222
01:32:04,452 --> 01:32:06,682
Does that mean he's not coming?
You promised us...

1223
01:32:06,854 --> 01:32:09,687
I know I promised you, Tommy,
but I just couldn't ask him.

1224
01:32:09,857 --> 01:32:12,087
The poor guy is going crazy
in Philadelphia.

1225
01:32:12,260 --> 01:32:15,286
The show isn't doing any business.
They're rewriting, recasting.

1226
01:32:15,463 --> 01:32:17,488
On top of all that, he twisted his ankle.

1227
01:32:17,665 --> 01:32:19,929
I had to sneak out of town myself.

1228
01:32:20,101 --> 01:32:23,502
Never mind, we'll put the show on,
it'll be great and he'll hear about it.

1229
01:32:23,671 --> 01:32:25,195
- Won't he, Jonesy?
- Overture's in.

1230
01:32:25,373 --> 01:32:27,603
Come on, Tommy, you're gonna be late.
Hurry up.

1231
01:32:27,775 --> 01:32:31,006
Everybody, come here for a minute.
Come on around me.

1232
01:32:31,178 --> 01:32:33,738
Come on. Wait a minute.
I got something to tell you.

1233
01:32:33,915 --> 01:32:37,544
This is the first time in years that
the curtain's gone up in the old Duchess.

1234
01:32:37,718 --> 01:32:40,084
Let's make them glad
they didn't tear it down, huh?

1235
01:32:40,254 --> 01:32:42,984
What do you say?
Come on, places, everybody!

1236
01:32:59,907 --> 01:33:02,774
<i>- Run for your lives!
- Stay where you are!</i>

1237
01:33:02,944 --> 01:33:05,435
<i>- Make a lot of noise!
- Keep still!</i>

1238
01:33:05,613 --> 01:33:11,279
<i>A bombshell just fell over Brazil</i>

1239
01:33:11,786 --> 01:33:14,550
<i>- Lay down your arms
- Run up your flags</i>

1240
01:33:14,722 --> 01:33:17,190
<i>You'll surrender to this jill</i>

1241
01:33:17,358 --> 01:33:21,488
<i>This bombshell that fell over Brazil</i>

1242
01:33:23,130 --> 01:33:28,295
<i>Her contribution
To the art of elocution</i>

1243
01:33:28,469 --> 01:33:34,430
<i>Is apt to start a revolution
Among the ladies at the Ritz</i>

1244
01:33:34,842 --> 01:33:40,371
<i>In Rio de Janeiro
When she sings "Mamae Eu Quero"</i>

1245
01:33:40,548 --> 01:33:46,919
<i>Every local caballero
Admits that it's a blitz</i>

1246
01:33:47,254 --> 01:33:50,189
<i>So give up the ship
Throw in the sponge</i>

1247
01:33:50,358 --> 01:33:53,020
<i>Get ready for a great big thrill</i>

1248
01:33:53,194 --> 01:33:58,461
<i>For here comes
That bombshell from Brazil</i>

1249
01:35:01,762 --> 01:35:03,195
Hey, Ma!

1250
01:35:06,067 --> 01:35:07,329
- How was it?
- Sensational.

1251
01:35:07,501 --> 01:35:10,493
- You murdered them.
- Come on, we only got a minute to change.

1252
01:35:10,671 --> 01:35:12,502
I was nervous.
I forgot the second chorus.

1253
01:35:12,840 --> 01:35:15,331
- You were great. Keep on being nervous.
- Don't forget...

1254
01:35:15,509 --> 01:35:18,307
- Who's Tommy Williams?
- I am.

1255
01:35:18,479 --> 01:35:21,812
I'm Inspector Moriarity.
Who are these two apples?

1256
01:35:21,982 --> 01:35:23,643
- They're my partners.
- Your partners?

1257
01:35:23,818 --> 01:35:25,251
What do you think you're doing?

1258
01:35:25,419 --> 01:35:28,183
We're in the middle of a number.
We're on stage in a minute.

1259
01:35:28,355 --> 01:35:30,380
- Come back around...
- Slow down, Mr. Ziegfeld.

1260
01:35:30,558 --> 01:35:32,822
- You ain't putting on any show.
- What do you mean?

1261
01:35:33,027 --> 01:35:34,824
- We're not putting on a show?
- Who says?

1262
01:35:34,995 --> 01:35:38,396
State of New York, City of New York,
board of health, and fire commission.

1263
01:35:38,566 --> 01:35:39,555
Shall I go on?

1264
01:35:39,734 --> 01:35:43,192
We're putting on a show. People
bought tickets. They're out in front now.

1265
01:35:43,370 --> 01:35:46,430
That's what I'm talking about.
You can't lock people in a firetrap.

1266
01:35:46,607 --> 01:35:48,575
This theatre's been condemned
for 15 years.

1267
01:35:48,743 --> 01:35:50,267
- I don't believe it.
- It's a plot.

1268
01:35:50,444 --> 01:35:54,312
Mr. Moriarity, you can't stop the show.
Please, don't stop it.

1269
01:35:54,482 --> 01:35:57,315
- Fifty little kids that never saw the sunlight.
- With rickets.

1270
01:35:57,485 --> 01:36:00,545
We've worked day and night like dogs,
like slaves. My mother, she...

1271
01:36:00,721 --> 01:36:03,189
I know all about the kids
and I've got a mother too...

1272
01:36:03,357 --> 01:36:07,919
...but if that audience isn't out of there in
15 minutes, I'll have to call the 8th Precinct.

1273
01:36:08,095 --> 01:36:11,861
- Mr. Moriarity, couldn't you...?
- I'm sorry, fellas, I know how you feel.

1274
01:36:12,032 --> 01:36:15,468
I almost was in a show myself once.

1275
01:36:29,483 --> 01:36:33,214
- Tommy. Tommy!
- Come in.

1276
01:36:33,387 --> 01:36:35,981
Come on. The orchestra's played
your cue three times.

1277
01:36:36,157 --> 01:36:38,216
Aren't you coming out on the stage?

1278
01:36:38,392 --> 01:36:43,830
Yeah, I'm coming out.

1279
01:36:43,998 --> 01:36:46,694
Bet I get a million laughs too.

1280
01:37:00,981 --> 01:37:02,846
Ladies and gentlemen...

1281
01:37:03,484 --> 01:37:08,717
...l'm terribly sorry,
but something unexpected has come up...

1282
01:37:08,889 --> 01:37:11,858
...and we will not be able
to continue the show.

1283
01:37:12,993 --> 01:37:18,397
It's some fire regulation or something
like that, something we knew nothing about.

1284
01:37:19,233 --> 01:37:23,795
And I'm awfully sorry that
we can't give the show...

1285
01:37:24,672 --> 01:37:29,632
...because it's really a wonderful show
and I'm sure that you would have all liked it.

1286
01:37:29,810 --> 01:37:35,214
Anyhow, we want to thank each and
every one of you for coming here...

1287
01:37:35,382 --> 01:37:38,977
...and having faith in us and trying to
help the send the kids to the country.

1288
01:37:40,154 --> 01:37:42,554
Everybody did their best.

1289
01:37:43,924 --> 01:37:49,226
So if you will stop by the box office
on your way out...

1290
01:37:49,463 --> 01:37:53,524
...why, your money will
be cheerfully refunded. Thank you.

1291
01:38:27,268 --> 01:38:30,897
Tommy, don't eat your heart out.

1292
01:38:31,071 --> 01:38:33,665
You did the best you could
and we're awful proud of you.

1293
01:38:33,841 --> 01:38:37,800
Yeah. Everybody did their best
and where did it get us?

1294
01:38:37,978 --> 01:38:39,570
Right out in left field.

1295
01:38:39,747 --> 01:38:42,580
No, don't help yourself,
help everybody else.

1296
01:38:42,750 --> 01:38:46,550
Be a Santa Claus, make sacrifices.
If you can do that for the rest of your life...

1297
01:38:46,720 --> 01:38:50,281
...you'll be a big success,
when you're about 165 years old.

1298
01:38:50,457 --> 01:38:52,584
- Tommy, you don't mean that.
- You can bet I do.

1299
01:38:52,760 --> 01:38:55,228
Where did it get us?
No money for the kids, no show...

1300
01:38:55,396 --> 01:38:58,092
...chance with Thornton Reed
blown right out of the window.

1301
01:38:58,265 --> 01:39:00,665
Tommy, you mustn't let it make you bitter,
please.

1302
01:39:00,834 --> 01:39:02,301
Faith, hope and charity.

1303
01:39:02,469 --> 01:39:06,098
Take those kids and wrap them in cellophane
and give them back to the Indians.

1304
01:39:06,273 --> 01:39:08,070
From now on, it's the old rules for me.

1305
01:39:08,242 --> 01:39:10,267
I'll get a chance again.
When I do, look out.

1306
01:39:10,444 --> 01:39:13,902
Because I'm gonna take anything
from anybody, at any time, any place.

1307
01:39:14,081 --> 01:39:16,174
- Tommy, l...
- No.

1308
01:39:30,331 --> 01:39:33,266
Mr. Williams.
They didn't take it. They didn't take it.

1309
01:39:33,434 --> 01:39:36,426
- Didn't take what?
- Come on, you tell him, Mr. Stone, tell him.

1310
01:39:36,603 --> 01:39:39,367
Tommy, it's amazing.
Everybody went right by the box office.

1311
01:39:39,540 --> 01:39:42,805
- They wouldn't take their money back.
- Some of them gave money besides.

1312
01:39:42,977 --> 01:39:45,946
Seven hundred and forty dollars.

1313
01:39:47,214 --> 01:39:50,081
Isn't it wonderful?
We got all the money to go to the country.

1314
01:39:50,250 --> 01:39:53,014
Now there's no need for putting
on a show at all.

1315
01:39:54,421 --> 01:39:59,620
Yeah. You're right.

1316
01:40:00,894 --> 01:40:03,829
There's no need in putting
